__label__NewZealand stand still. the trees ahead and bushes beside you
are not lost. wherever you are is called here,
and you must treat it as a powerful stranger,
must ask permission to know it and be known.
the forest breathes. listen. it answers.
if what a tree or a bush does is lost on you,
you are surely lost. stand still. the forest knows
where you are. you must let it find you.
#lost #davidwagoner heard this poem read on a podcast this morning and instantly my mind was transported back to this moment in a forest far away 🌲🍃 pc: @kelsealoha

__label__Hawaii #capitalonepartner i’m very excited to be partnering with @capitalone this year on a series of posts - how to spend, save and invest more wisely. of course all of my tips will be travel-based! 
my first post is now live: the ultimate pre-travel checklist. it’s at capital.one/2t420f2 and linked at my profile. i thought through everything that i do before every trip – some money-based, like knowing the foreign exchange rate and having a credit card that doesn’t charge foreign transaction fees, but also things like checking passport expiration dates, looking into insurance and vaccinations, memorizing a few words in the local language, and getting the house ready. and i created a downloadable checklist to make it easy for you to check things off before your next trip. that way you can enjoy your beach vacation instead of stressing! this was earlier this year in hawaii. 
i’d love feedback. is there anything i’m missing? how do you keep track of everything you need to do before you leave?

#smartmoney #takeyourkidseverywhere

__label__Canada a dream come true- watching the sun rise over floe lake high in the canadian rockies. i do all my work outside, the seasons pace it, and i work with @canonusa to document the shift between them. nothing makes an alpine photograph like a massive peak reflected on a lake, and this goes back hundreds of years in paintings. in photography it’s a little different because it needs to happen for you capture it.. to make sure the odds are on my side, i check the weather forecast and look for low winds. i wake up way before sunrise, usually the rise of the sun brings thermal winds. and lastly, i pick a low vantage point over the water to maximize the reflection of the landscape on it.. nothing scientific, just prep and a healthy dose of patience. shot on #eos80d with 10-18mm stm lens.

__label__ChiangMai,Thailand while your sitting there telling yourself you can't do something, there's someone else saying you can.
.
.
there's also someone else out there telling themselves they can do something and having the life you want. self doubt is a hard monkey to shake. it'll cling onto you and not let go. it'll engulf you if you let it. .
.
what helps me is small, baby steps. small goals, that once completed, make me feel better. completing these small goals gives me the confidence to make the goals bigger. and before i know it, i've crushed those goals too. .
.
look, nobody can tell you "don't doubt yourself!" and it really stick. you have to realize it for yourself. you can read all the motivational quotes in the world, but if you don't believe it in you, life will never change. .
.
i'll just say this, if this guy can accomplish his dreams, literally anyone can. boy oh boy, if y'all knew the old me.....if i can come out of that alive and keep fighting, you can too. trust me there. .
.
so keep fighting. there's alot to fight for.

__label__Florence,Italy the other day, i posted about indecision. i struggle with it quite often, but as of late, i’ve understood that when we don’t decide, we don’t move forward. it is only when we make decisions, and take actions towards them, that our life can transform for the better. for example:
⠀⠀⠀ ⠀
i decided i would change my life and live it my way, and i did.
⠀⠀⠀ ⠀
i decided that i could circumnavigate the world, and that i’d do so successfully, and that’s exactly what happened.
⠀⠀⠀ ⠀
i decided that humanity was good, and it has treated me kindly.
⠀⠀⠀ ⠀
none of this happened, nor could have happened, until i decided it was going to. and once i did… it was like i flipped a magic switch. i started getting what i wanted from life, and it flowed to me in abundance.
⠀⠀⠀ ⠀
stop sitting on the fence. whatever you’re thinking about, whatever you want with your life… either commit to doing it, or don’t.
⠀⠀⠀ ⠀
if you make a mistake, you can always adjust course. but if you do nothing, you’ll just be in limbo, constantly oscillating from one possibility to the next and wondering “what if.”
⠀⠀⠀ ⠀
decide what you want, and go for it. why live life in-between?
⠀⠀⠀ ⠀

__label__Iceland once we'd had our fill of mývatn, we headed south and west before turning north to drive along eyjafjörður. we stopped at the stunning goðafoss waterfall (which @dante.vincent has just posted an awesome photo of) but a lot of the drive aside from that waterfall seemed less exciting to me. when compared to everywhere else we'd been. there was some intermittent rain, some gray sky and i just couldn't wait to get up to the fjord, able to see the ocean again. as we got closer to the water there was this moment where we were coming downhill, a whole valley stretching out before us, when the sun broke through the clouds, the sky was no longer gray and i yelled out that we had to, "stop the car!" sometimes you don't plan photos, you don't even create them, they just present themselves and demand to be taken...

__label__LagunaBeach,California they say you are an average of the five people you spend the most time with. what do you think about that? whether it’s friends, family, co-workers, or whoever else you choose to spend your days with, the people around you mold who you are. it’s important to be open to change too. i’ve learned as you go through stages of your life, those five people may change, but true friendships always endure. i think one of the most important things you can do is always challenge yourself. when i was training to play professional tennis i always tried to practice with people better than me. it wasn’t easy and i often got pushed around the court, but i learned so much and got better quick. same parallels in photography/video. learn from others who inspire you, but take aspects of things you love and create your own style. the same goes both ways. make sure you’re teaching and inspiring others just as much. there’s so much to learn as you navigate through your life, but helping others is often just as rewarding as self-improvement.

__label__HoChiMinhCity,Vietnam our final stop on our @busaboutasia tour - ho chi minh city/saigon!!! we've been here for a couple days and have done and seen so much already. i have so many things i want to share about this city, especially given its unfortunate history with america, and some things i've noticed in regards to that.

but before i address that, here are some fun facts to help contextualize the monstrosity of this city and the uniqueness it encompasses.

1. it's the largest city in vietnam and was formerly the capital of the french colony of cochinchina. because of this, you see so much western influence, and the beauty and juxtaposition of asian and french architecture is absolutely stunning. this is also the only city in vietnam with a mcdonald's! #murica

2. the languages spoken include vietnamese, cantonese, teochew, hokkien, hainanese and hakka dialects of chinese, mandarin, and english.

3. over 3 million people visit ho chi minh city every year, which accounts for nearly 70% of all tourism in vietnam.

4. hcmc's population is over 9 million and expected to rise to almost 14 million in 10 years due to it being the economic center where people from the north migrate for work.

5. yellow traffic lights literally mean to speed up, not slow down. but there are essentially no rules on the road. you could legitimately set out a picnic in the middle of the busiest roundabout in this city and you will go untouched.

these are the craziest yet most efficient drivers i have ever seen. toddlers, refrigerators, bags of rice, or live chicken hanging by the feet are all normal things you might see on the backseat of a motorbike. can't wait to share footage!

this city, simply put, is unreal and excuse my inability to form comprehensive sentences to adequately summarize my thoughts. still allowing myself to process this magnetic environment. more soon. what a city. what a country. ❤

__label__Lofoten taking a leap into the unknown is scary. we can plan for it, believe in ourselves, predict various potential outcomes, and yet... we still have no guarantees that it’ll work out.
⠀⠀⠀ ⠀
there is an element of uncertainty in everything that we do. every day, we are taking risks: we can walk outside and get hit by a car, awkwardly run into an ex, be unexpectedly fired, the list goes on.
⠀⠀⠀ ⠀
so what gives - why is going after what you truly want any scarier than staying where you already are?
⠀⠀⠀ ⠀
i get it. the closer you get to what you want, the more unbearable the uncertainty feels. and guess what - it’s ok to feel that way, and then move past that feeling.
⠀⠀⠀ ⠀
you are already taking a risk by being a breathing, living organism operating in your current conditions, so why not make decisions that could actually change your life for the better?
⠀⠀⠀ ⠀
kiss that person, ask for that raise, start that business. try it despite the uncertainty and give it your best. maybe even fail at it. then get up, and try again.
⠀⠀⠀ ⠀
the possibilities for success are infinite, and our time is finite.
⠀⠀⠀ ⠀
you will never know how your leap of faith works out. but you will know that you gave this life your best, and that in itself makes any risk worth it.
⠀⠀⠀ ⠀

__label__Athens,Greece how gorgeous can an aerial shot get!? greece, you have my heart. see you again in july! 😍

sidenote: @aegeanairlines has some of the best airline food i've ever tasted.

i checked the "kosher" option, mainly because it sounded sophisticated, and i'm not, and irony is fun 😂

anyway, on my connection to athens i had meatballs, tomatoes, bread, and sliced carrots with cookies.

on my connection to cyprus, i had salmon with diced potatoes, a jar of salmon rilettes, and i sh*t you not, applesauce.

i have never seen applesauce in europe. let alone eaten any in america since i was like 12. this was such an emotional moment for me. life, like... can you not!?! 😭

and then a vanilla cream cookie sandwich to balance out my pending die-of-beetus.

if you haven't been keeping up with me on snapchat, you're missing all the fun! 👻 gl0 (with a cheerio, i mean zero 😂). 

p.s. 5 hours until the winner of the #iwanttobusabout contest is announced! meeeeeeep! 🙊

__label__Prague,CzechRepublic before visiting #prague for the first time this week, i googled #travelblogger reviews and i was a little taken aback by the number of reviews from black #bloggers who considered #czechs in the city to be racist because of their cold stares, etc. but being here (and coming from usa tbh) i've found that to be personally untrue (especially compared to usa). how have we come to the point that we construe a long glance from another human a negative action? a stare really could mean 'hello', 'fuck you', or 'let's fuck'. imo eye contact is really the most primative form of #communication. an expression of curiosity from which you can determine a fight or flight response, etc. #blackisbeautiful and people naturally stare at beautiful things. so why not reply with a #smile instead of suspicion? it's worked for me so far.

__label__ElNido,Palawan postales de filipinas.
⚐ ubicación: el nido, palawan
sus 3 playas principales son:
-el nido beach: es la playa del centro de la ciudad, rodeada de restaurantes y bares muy al estilo asía. desde acá salen todas las excursiones
-corong corong. esta a solo 10min en tuc tuc. la recomendamos mucho porque es más linda y tranquila que la playa del centro y tiene varios spots para ver el atardecer, muy accesible alquilar kayaks, hacerte masajes o relajarte tomando algo frente al mar
-las cabañas beach. a 15min en tuc tuc se encuentra la playa más linda de el nido. agua cristalina con bares sobre la playa para tomar algo fresco y disfrutar sus increíbles vistas
☆ alojamiento? neela tourist lodge.
♔ tip: el nido se caracteriza por sus tour. si tenes un día, definitivamente el a, aunque el c también es una muy buena opción. 
no te pierdas el atardecer en republica sunset que es una pasada!
.
¿estuviste por el nido? 
déjanos tus tips para próximos viajeros!
-
memories from the philippines.
⚐ location: el nido, palawan (the main attraction of this region). the beaches are:
-the nest beach: the town beach, surrounded by asian style restaurants and bars. every excursion departs from here.
-corong corong: 10min in tuc tuc from town. here we stayed and we super recommended. it is prettier and quieter than the beach in the center and has several spots to enjoy the sunset, rent a kayak (like the one in our photo) or have a massage.
-las cabanyas. 15min in tuc tuc will take to reach the most beautiful beach of el nido. crystal clear water with beach bars to drink something fresh and enjoy its incredible views
☆ accommodation? neela tourist lodge.
♔ tip: el nido is characterized by its tours. if you have a day, definitely the a, although the c is also a very good option.
don’t miss the sunset in republica sunset that is stunning!
.

__label__Cappadocia/Kapadokya i really tried to narrow down these pictures but it was impossible. cappadocia, turkey in the winter is one of the most magical places i’ve visited. it has been on my bucket list for years and i’m so glad i went. 
cappadocia is located pretty much in the middle of the country. it’s a quick 80min flight from istanbul making it an easy weekend trip. the region is geographically beautiful and probably most well known for its phallic looking rock formations otherwise known as “fairy chimneys.” i visited the area back in 2012 in the spring and at that time spent a few days visiting the göreme open air museum and the rock churches with beautifully preserved mosaics that the region is known for. we hiked a bit and visited the underground cities and went hot air ballooning. it was amazing. 
then a couple years later i saw pictures on a travel blog of hot air ballooning in the winter and i wanted to go back ever since. i wanted to see the region blanketed in snow. cappadocia is the hot air ballooning capital of the world. but hot air ballooning is unpredictable. it’s so weather dependant. if it’s windy you can’t fly and so on the morning of my scheduled flight i was tempted to reschedule seeing as it was -21c but i knew i’d risk not getting to go at all. so i bundled up and took a few hundred pictures. every view was amazing. the rising sun coming up against the landscape with balloons doting the horizon was mesmerizing. 
the rest of the two days i spend there were mostly just to relax. i sipped wine by the fire. read. did some writing and lazily soaked in an amazing deep soaking tub. it was perfect!

__label__Bali,Indonesia networking up: when's the last time you reached out to someone who was 10x more powerful than you?

how intimidating was it and did your email have 💩 smears from the virtual pants-sh*tting?

i recently had to look at my network and reach out to the 10 most powerful people in it and ask for a favor, because with these new goals i have, i'm not foolish to think i will ever get there on my own.

it'll require others to vouch for me, connect with me, and constructively criticize me and i can't tell you how humbled i've been by it.

i'm not a name-dropper, but i'm blessed to know a few millionaires on a first-name basis.

in comparison, lil' ol me has nothing of equal weight to offer, but here's why they respond to my requests 99% of the time.

i treat them like a human, not a dollar amount.

i respect their time.

i don't assume a yes.

i've interacted or engaged with them dozens of times without ever asking for anything.

i've supported their work in the past.

i share my goals and my mission.

i let them know how grateful i am for their time/consideration, even if they can't help.

one thing that's the most disheartening about people who email me asking for favors, is that they do none of the above.

they treat me like a step on a ladder/a way of getting ahead.

they demand a response immediately.

they assume a yes.

they've never engaged with a single social media post.

they've never supported my work.

they don't share their goals.

they rarely answer back after i've helped them out.

e-mail etiquette is a thing y'all. study it and implement those habits into your everyday virtual interactions.

the same goes for dms and fb messenger.

there are ways to network with powerful people, you just need to learn to come correct.

feel free to drop any other tips below!

photo credit | @dearalyne

__label__PhiPhiIslands i celebrate myself, but the celebration remains in my head. 
i am the only one who knows about it; for it remains unsaid.

if i pranced around saying, "i love me", i would lose all respect, that is a guarantee. 
to celebrate such a silly thing as myself, it would be rude to the nature and her wealth.

we should not celebrate the ever-changing personalities, but clap our hands in appreciation of the ever lasting amenities.

though, if i were to celebrate such a silly thing, i would compare myself to that of a songbird's wing.
.
.

⚐ubicación: corón
esta en una isla a la que se llega en barco o avión desde el nido.
lugar increíble por sus lagunas de agua verde rodeadas de rocas enormes, y genial para bucear en barcos japoneses hundidos en la segunda guerra mundial
☆alojamiento: lan bless pensión house
estuvo bien pero nos quedamos con ganas de “kalachuchi hostel for divers”. el dueño es muy buena onda, español e instructor de buceo
♔tip: los tours en coron están organizado para que pagues más de uno para ver las atracciones principales pero podes alquilar un barco entre varios y así ahorrar y elegir los lugares que querés visitar (imperdible el kayangan lake)

no dudes en escribirnos para más info!

memories from philippines 🇵🇭
⚐location: coron
it’s on an island that can be reached by boat or plane from el nido.
amazing place for its green water lagoons surrounded by huge rocks, and great for diving in japanese shipwrecks from world war ii
☆ accommodation: lan bless pension house. it was fine but we were looking forward to "kalachuchi hostel for divers". the owner is from spain, very nice and with good diving tips.
♔tip: the tours in coron are organized so that you pay more than one to see the main attractions but you can rent a boat for your own and choose the places you want to visit (kayangan lake is definitely a must do)

__label__Iceland inspired by a fresh start to the new year, i wrote a blog post about how my main goal for 2017 is to *actually* start all the projects i've been meaning to do for years. i'm one of those people who has trouble starting because i’m afraid that i’ll fail - which is pretty much the worst reason ever not to tackle a new project. in fact, i bet many of us are like that - starting something new, especially a creative venture, without any idea of how it'll turn out, is pretty freaking daunting, right? like the book i want to write. what if it’s terrible? and not only terrible, what if it’s the worst book in the entire world? well, i might as well not even try, right? no! we should create for the simple joy of just making something, not for the success. which always reminds me of iceland. did you know iceland is consistently ranked one of the world's happiest countries? and one reason, i believe, is because of their creativity. iceland has the most published authors per capita of anywhere in the world. people write books to write books, to have an outlet for their creativity. they also drink a lot. so i reckon let’s drink more and be like iceland. i mean create. let’s create more. and actually take that leap of faith and begin a new project 📷 @tinyiceland

__label__Seattle,Washington you ever just get down on yourself for all the things you aren’t doing with your life, or all the things you haven’t accomplished yet? 
it happens to me often actually and sometimes i just have to sit with myself and remember my purpose and passions are in me for a reason. on this fine tuesday i woke up feeling like i had more power than i ever give myself credit for, i have the power to be patient with myself and know that in less than 4 months i will be able to say i am doing what i feel i’m meant to do. but even if you’re not sure what that is yet, don’t ever compare your life to someone else’s because you get to control how you live yours. don’t give that power to anyone else. trust the universe, trust god, trust yourself that you are living and breathing and doing you just perfectly in your own way ✨🐝

__label__Lofoten one of the biggest issues i've had to overcome as a photographer that travels the globe is to learn awareness of the issues facing the places i love & have dedicated my life to documenting. i cringe to think of the times in my life where i've photographed something purely for its beauty while failing to mention that it's under threat & in need of protection. which is why my work documenting iceland's rivers have been more than just an artistic endeavor for likes. .
the latest issue that has been brought to my attention from the many passionate locals & incredible messages from people like you - is the potential for oil drilling in norway's lofoten islands as well as other neighboring locations. 
i cannot express the beauty & importance of this wild place & as always i hope you do your own research & form an educated decision. if you have been inspired by this landscape then i urge you to speak out as the window to be heard is now.
.

negotiations to open the area for drilling start after sept 11 & the fate of this landscape falls upon the 
norwegian prime minister candidates @jonasgahrs & @erna_solberg . feel free to tag them in a comment expressing your position or express your feelings to them directly. for more info check out www.lovese.no

face mapping is a holistic tool that has been practiced for centuries. if you find yourself breaking out on your cheeks, this could be the reason why: ✨
organ connections: lungs, kidneys
underlying issue: poor absorption, dental hygiene ✨
pollution, smoking, poor food choices and asthma can all contribute to breakouts on the cheeks. it is also possible the body is having a hard time assimilating and /or metabolizing the foods you eat. one way to work with this is to increase your nutrients through freshly prepared green juices. increasing nutrients and decreasing processed, starchy and unwholesome foods can help kick start your digestive system and clear up acne on the cheeks. ✨
practices to clear cheek acne
be mindful of overeating. learn how to decipher hunger from thirst. notice how often you snack or eat when emotionally charged or bored. 
consider resting your eyes a few times a day. how often are you reading, staring, working or looking?  closing the eyes to rest can be a simple practice to turn in and rejuvenate all the senses. 
do not wait for your dentist to tell you how important it is to floss! 
clean all cell phones and pillowcases regularly to stay clear of dirt and bacteria buildup

__label__Sydney,Australia top 🐨ty weather! 😏
••••••••••••••••••••••••••••••••••••••••••••••••
it might sound weird, but i often prefer to photograph myself. i still get camera shy if someone is shooting me. and, i am a photographer at heart. so it’s a fun challenge to be creative with how i shoot. for photos like this, i set up my tripod and put my camera on an interval timer setting to take a photo every second for 50 photos and then pick my favorite from the batch. i am able to get my composition and lighting right before pressing the shutter and jumping into frame. i probably look like a crazy tourist but it feels more natural for me and i end up looking way more comfortable in photos.

a few quick tips for self-shooting:
1. don’t be embarrassed. they’re your memories and you can’t expect someone to always be there to capture them for you.
2. read up on the rule of 3rds. it’s not the end-all-be-all of composition, but it’s a good guideline to work from (you’ll understand why i was so satisfied with my lines in this shot— thanks 🐦!)
3. don’t skip the edit. i shoot in raw (it gives more flexibility with your post-processing) and use my lightroom @tbapresets for desktop and mobile!

__label__RiodeJaneiro,RiodeJaneiro are you coming with us to down to brazil for rio carnival 2019!? join us!! when i was building this trip to rio i scored a behind the scenes pass at the cidade do samba, the warehouse where some of the top schools prepare their floats, costumes and choreography for the  biggest party on earth!

along with the tour i got to learn the original history of samba and carnival. not the white-washed version we all get because we are disconnected from our international brothers and sisters. 
did you know that carnival, the half a 600 million dollar yearly parade in rio de janeiro, is largely existing because of one black slave woman that wasn’t afraid to break the rules?

the legend states that tia ciata migrated from bahia, brazil down to rio with many other freed slaves in 1875. being that there were little to no places for blacks to congregate publicly, ciata began hosting parties in her house where her community could eat, play music, dance, and fellowship. 
these parties held in the favelas of rio are where the original rhythms of samba were developed. to make this story even more black, these illegal parties were always getting shut down by the.cops for being too lit and too black. 
aside from the perfect host, ciata was also known as a great chef and to have great healing powers as a local leader of the condoblé (dance in honor of the gods) religion. she sold baked treats on the streets of rio and became a mini celebrity for her food, religious ceremonies, and parties at her house. 
the legend continues that one day the late brazilian  president venceslau brás called upon her to heal his leg and in return he appointed her husband to the chief of police. 
he decided to continue to keep her parties publicly illegal, however he allotted them to use  a phone in their home that would warn them of police nearby. 
as ciata continued to build the samba scene, it attracted many famous insiders and journalists. “pelo telefone” by ernesto dos santos became the first ever recorded samba song. it was produced in ciata’s house in little africa, a small neighborhood in central rio. .

__label__LosAngeles,California [7/12] it’s nearly impossible to get your first 5,000 subscribers. we remember saying once we reach 8,000 followers, we’ll be happy. there was no real reason; it just sounded like a big number.
〰
our days were spent trying not to fall asleep in college lectures (until damon dropped out - jo stuck it out for the last two years, since she had free room & board in manhattan). our nights were spent at grind coworking on 23rd and park, where we would meet after our day-jobs. jo strategically got a front desk job so we could use the space after-hours to edit our videos. damon taught french classes at fluent city in brooklyn, so we could have access to free language classes.
〰
our youtube paychecks for the first two years were minimal - literally $1 a day. we did everything from walking a cute-ass dog named gypsy for a fashion designer in chelsea. we delivered groceries with instacart because the app was so beta that nobody placed any orders, which meant we could get paid while editing our videos. there was also a three-day stint at johnny rockets for damon, and an instance where jo walked out on her boss at serafina in the meatpacking district.
〰
the real money was in new york city catering, where we’d get emotional when the bride and groom would play their engagement video, as if we were invited to the wedding. we’d eat their cake and clap at the father-daughter dance. we’d offer tuna tartar and sometimes accidentally spill starter salads on people. the highlight was $22/hour, plus a hefty tip from manhattan’s upper crust.
〰
and during all these jobs, we’d find time to scrap money together, buy cheap bus tickets to random cities like baltimore, film, edit, and hope for the best after clicking publish. we were disappointing everyone: our bosses, our friends, our lovers, our sleep-deprived eyeballs, but we knew it's what we had to do.
〰
our channel wasn’t made overnight.

__label__Budapest,Hungary budapest, the capital of hungary 🇭🇺
⠀
the hungarian parliament building is one of the most beautiful in the world. the architecture is striking as are the details.
⠀
it’s especially beautiful from the other side of the danube river, but i like this angle too as it’s another perspective that you don’t see in photos too often.
⠀
i’ve been to budapest more times than i can count with my hands, and it’s easily one of my favorite cities in europe.
⠀
of course i’m a bit biased due to my hungarian heritage, but the city has it all. the best period to visit according to me is somewhere in may/june before it gets crowded in the summer.

__label__Bali one of our flaws is that we only value things that feel scarce. daily routines can often lose meaning and value when they feel limitless. sometimes even a beautiful sunset on the way home from work can feel unimportant because “there will always be another”. a few years ago i began reminding myself every single time i watched the sunset that it could literally be the last time i ever witness it. 
i have never had a greater appreciation for the way the colours change and the sunlight bounces. i try to apply this same thinking to everything that i do and it has always brought a greater appreciation for the moments and things around me. 
even if it’s from the drivers seat of your car on the way home from work, watch your next sunset like it could be your last and i can guarantee you, you will have a new found appreciation for the colours in the sky 🌅
mansionair - astronaut 🎵

__label__Honolulu,Hawaii throughout my travels around the world, i am consistently reminded of what it really means to go with the flow. theoretically, flowing should be an easy and smooth process - if you let it. but to most of us, flowing doesn’t come naturally; we have to learn to find inner equilibrium within circumstances that are consistently shifting beyond our control.
.
paddle yoga strangely taught me a lesson on what it means to go with the flow. when the wind blows you a certain direction, don’t fight it - focus on feeling its breeze. when the ground shifts beneath your feet, remember to find your balance. when your surroundings feel strange and unfamiliar, ease yourself into them until they become comfortable. and never forget to occasionally dip your fingers into the water and feel the vast ocean that carries you.
.
challenge yourself. let the flow take you to where you need to be. you may fall off your paddle sometimes, but the good news is, you can always get back up.
.
not pictured: me doing a dope headstand on the paddle board. sadly i looked too awkward to post it 😂.
.
thank you @yogakaihawaii for the amazing session!
.

__label__HongKong photography / instagram tips - always have a clear subject.
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
if you want to get the attention of the viewer, the photo can’t be too messy. you only have 1 second before the viewer has judged your photo in their head. after that, you have either caught their attention or lost it.
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
if you have a clear subject, it’s easy to look at the photo and by having a main subject in clear focus, you will get the viewer’s attention.
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
take this photo for example, the ding ding tram is my main subject, but there are lots of other interesting stuff in the photo as well. however, the other things don’t steal the attention at first glance.
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
for me, the local lady and skyscrapers are equally interesting, but you will most likely take a look at these after you’ve seen the main subject - the ding ding tram.
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
in photography, and a lot of things in life, less is often more. i often see people wanting to photograph and get everything in the frame, but that can easily make the photo messy.
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
i will keep sharing photography and instagram tips in every second photo i post 🙂
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
if you have a special request for tips or questions, leave a comment!

__label__London,UnitedKingdom voy a tenerlo todo y no me da vergüenza ni miedo decirlo, es muy importante estar enfocados, escucharnos, tomar conciencia de las señales. esos mensajes que no tienen sentido, borrosos, difusos, que te paralizan a hacer lo que hay que hacer, quererte de verdad, tomar la decisión.somos poderosos, no te contraigas, nada es suficiente y todo es posible de ser creado.todo tu ser, todo tu cuerpo los sabe, que esa decisión, que parece una locura es lo que estuviste creando y bloqueando por querer “pertenecer”.lo que nadie te dice, lo que nadie te pregunta es si te alcanza con eso para ser feliz.cuanto más me alejo de todas las estructuras, cuanto más destruyo las cajitas de cristal, más me siento feliz, ¡ridículamente feliz!el mensaje siempre es, fue y será claro, está ahí, latente, lo sabemos con todas nuestras fibras aunque a veces preferimos no verlo.somos potencial, somos magia, nada pasa porque sí, todo lo creamos y si la locura más grande te lleva a dónde quieres estar entonces ¡adelante!, salta, arriésgate a ver todo tu potencial ilimitado.
.
¡feliz vida, feliz viaje! ✈️🙌 📷foto: gisela escales/ @gisela_escales

__label__Amsterdam,Netherlands i spent 5 blissful 'do nothing' days in amsterdam. long, purposeless walks along the canals of the city. people-watching. browsing quirky stores. reading murakami on a park bench for hours. leaching on to free social wifi by liking a facebook page to check emails. .
.
i loved the feeling of anonymity. no camera, no photos (except some food photos with my iphone 😝). no agenda. no meetings. no one to catch up with. no commitments. just me and my thoughts. my solitude even in the crowded cobbled streets, even in empty alleyways. .
.
i loved slow, delicious meals at hip vegan cafes... including @roots_amsterdam @laviniagoodfood @dophertamsterdam and @vegabondfood 🍔 this meal at dophert, with a burger patty made of chickpeas and topped with chipotle mayo, and sweet potato fries with lemon mayo... just yum! .
.
and well, the seriously incredible feeling of walking into a coffeeshop and being asked, "what kind of high are you in the mood for?" the epitome of freedom, if you ask me 🎉 .
.
so yes, 5 blissful days that went by in a blur. and yesterday, i arrived in... wait for it... scotland! ✈️
.
.
got any memories of aimless city wanderings to share?

__label__Kauai all photography, to a certain extent, is a lie. a friend said that to me the other day during a conversation about photoshop and my first impulse was to disagree. but in there somewhere was a seed of truth i mulled over today as i edited. photography is the photographer's imposition and framing of reality. it's the color corrected stopping of time. 
it's confusing and beautiful. manipulative and transportive. is it more important for an image to tell the truth or the truth as i experienced it? this image, for example, you would never know photographer @mikecoots and i were getting absolutely hammered by wind and current. that this was the one area with semi clear water. the lens was finicky and the focus on me is a bit soft. normally that would drive me insane, but it felt right for this one. for the reality i wanted to tell. it was a fun albeit imperfect adventure. does it lose its magic when i tell the truth? does anyone even read a caption this long? 😂sorry, these are the things i think about when i sit at the computer for hours :) #onedayillwriteashortcaption

__label__GrandCanyonNationalPark i remember 10 year ago when i just moved to the states, one of my biggest desires was to be fluent in english. it was so important to me that i even wrote it on piece of paper among other important things that i wanted to accomplish.
just imagine moving to a foreign country without speaking the language. you are not just moving there for a week or a month, you are moving there to start your new life, so you have to do something to provide for yourself, you don’t have anybody to rely on - you are on your own. you know that you are a grown person and you can express yourself perfectly in your own language, you can communicate with others and articulate anything. 
when you come to a foreign land everything shifts, you feel like you are almost a new born in a body of an adult, you can move around and do things physically, but you cannot communicate well with others. all you can do is smile and pretend like you understand something and sometimes it can be very awkward when people ask you a question and you answer “yes” , where you supposed to say “no”, because you didn’t understand the question. at that moment the look on their face is priceless.
😁

__label__Bali,Indonesia who else here lives a life teetering between two extremes?

is it the aries in me? my extroverted introversion? my quarter-life crisis talking?

i'm convinced there's a good chunk of us who go through life trying so hard to listen to the "right" voice when there's 10 others that try to take center stage.

in a world that's very black and white to everyone else, how do you walk the fine line of gray?

we are such passionate souls that we know no middle ground in anything.

we either love something with all our hearts, or reject it with every fiber of our souls.

we either want to be jiggin' in the middle of the dance floor, or completely isolated in the middle of nowhere.

we either want to make close connections to break down our walls, or keep everyone at a 10-foot distance.

why tho?

i've been opening up about these revelations to a handful of friends and it's so empowering to know i'm not alone.

as we blink our eyes and end up in december, it's crazy to think about all the goals we set for ourselves just 11 months back, and how much we've hit or missed the mark since then.

2018 will come with its fair share of life lessons, serendipitous encounters, and dream-chasing, and i hope like hell, i'm ready for it all.

speaking of the new year, if i invited like 4 of you to celebrate new year's eve with me somewhere in central or south america, where should we go? 🤔 #seriousquestion 
#andhowdoichoose

__label__Marrakech happy hump day!

wednesdays are becoming my new fridays, because i can start planning my weekend and get motivated to finish tasks and tackle my never-ending inbox. and while it's easy to think travelers or people who live abroad are on an endless vacation, the truth is that we go through our slumps just like we would back home. routines get old, you crave new adventures, and you question every detail of your life just like i would be back in the states. living in another country doesn't make me immune to the quarter-life crisis which i'll be facing in a month. 25 years old, wow! and while my biological clock is probably ticked off (#pleaseseewhatididthere), i don't foresee myself giving up this lifestyle any time soon. at least when all my friends' kids reach high school, they can babysit my toddler 😂😩😭 #gimme10moreyears

__label__Norway meet my friend, johann. 🦌 johann is a reindeer living in norway's arctic tundra. also, he definitely isn't named johann, i just have a habit of naming every animal i meet and he gave off sort of a "johann-esque" kind of vibe.
.
i'd love to tell you all about the magical time that i had hanging out with johann, feeding him pellets and brushing his soft downy reindeer fur and laughing together about how my hair was frozen because it was -30 degrees outside. but that's not what happened.
.
you see, johann is not yet domesticated, and as a result is very shy around people. a few days before i met him, was living a happy reindeer life in the wild, not realizing that his very existence was made possible by indigenous sámi reindeer herders who spend countless hours moving his herd from place to place so that they stay safe from predators and well fed.
.
so johann is still adapting to life as a domestic reindeer. his herders will spend a week or so getting to know him, walking him on a leash, and feeding him pellets while he learns that they mean him no harm. and so because johann wasn't comfortable around me, i refrained from touching him, as pettable and adorable as he looked with his little face and his little horns and those big eyes. instead, i left him some pellets and took a zillion photos of him from a reasonable distance.
.
the sami people have been living in the arctic of modern-day norway, finland, sweden and russia for thousands of years, practicing reindeer husbandry and herding. today, only about 2,800 sami reindeer herders remain, working together to keep their traditions (and their herds) alive. on my trip to norway, i was lucky enough to spend 3 days in the tundra getting to know a family of sámi reindeer herders and learning about the choices they make every day to preserve their heritage and culture. today (feb 6) is sami national day, a holiday celebrated by all sami people across their various country borders. happy sami national day!
.
did you know that there are still indigenous people living in the arctic tundra? have you ever met a reindeer? drop your comments and questions below!
.
#visitnatives #visitnorway #impacttravelalliance

feliz noche familia😘😘😘

__label__SanFrancisco,California spent the day in san francisco with @a.study.in.charlotte, another friend i made on instagram. it's crazy how many people i've met through my social network since i set off on my couch-surfing social experiment 7 months ago. everywhere i visit, there is a new person to meet: and more likely than not, i end up really liking them and wanting to stay friends moving forward.
.
i suppose that's how one can make friends all over the world - by putting yourself out there, being vulnerable, and open-minded to new and often unexpected encounters. believe that people will be kind and good, and i can personally vouch that they usually are!
.

__label__Bali,Indonesia “when you have more than you need, build a longer table, not a higher fence.” your platform is in vain if you amass riches and do nothing to give back.

because of my recent @forbes article (almost 20,000 hits, wow!) and @dearalyne video (620,000 views 😭), it’s been inspiring to see how many people of color have hit me up, as there’s not nearly enough representation of us in the travel media space.

so i’ve been sending tips, pointers, and advice all weekend.

but! if information alone made us rich, we’d all be billionaires.

it’s information, application, and dedication that are the three components to success, so i hope these 3 quick tips will give further inspiration and context.

1. change your circle.

we’ve all heard the quote by jim rohn, “you’re the average of the 5 people you spend the most time with.” i didn’t truly understand the power of that until i made it a goal this year to aim to be the dumbest person in the room.

that sounds foolish, but think about it — how are you growing if you’re always the one giving information?

i had to start connecting with people who not only made more money than me, but had more experience in more areas.

you don’t have to cut everyone out of your life, just be a bit more selective with who you’re giving your best energy to.

2. start journaling.

i started journaling because i was constantly throwing myself into foreign territory — whether the food, the currency, or the culture, everything about my life was a never-ending cycle of adaptation.

i needed some way to center myself and meditation and journaling was the best answer.

3. take money out of the equation.

this sounds counterintuitive, but i need people to understand that if you’re in a profession solely for the money and perks, then you’ll never truly be happy or satisfied.

how i know blogging is for me? because i’d still be doing it if i never made a single dollar from it.

i started my first blog when i was 11, and even though my hard-hitting content was about cute boys at my school 😅 i developed a voice and sense of liberation from feeling like there was a corner of the internet i could call my own.

tag someone who could use this info below! ❤

__label__RiodeJaneiro,RiodeJaneiro the only thing more electric than the sunrise was watching the city come alive to start the day. rio de janeiro was so much more than i expected. it was mountains erupting from the city. it was people enjoying the beaches up and down the coastline. it was an energy i haven’t felt before. 4am wake up calls are always rough, but moments like these make the journey from a comfy bed 100% worth it.

__label__AbuDhabi,UnitedArabEmirates 🇦🇪✈️🇦🇪 the presidential palace with emirates palace creeping in the shot. a lot of you have asked me whether to come to dubai or abu dhabi. to be honest, they are very different. abu dhabi is the capital and much more conservative. sure everyone knows it for the cool abu dhabi grand prix and the red bull air race, and there are some great things to do here like ferrari world, but if you want everything bigger (and more varied, then head to dubai) 🐪 water parks, bigger malls, fountain shows and many more restaurants and bars/clubs. i personally came to abu dhabi just to get sun and work done, but if i wanted a more ‘active’ holiday with more options, there’s certainly more to do in dubai. don’t forget though, they are only 1.5hr drive apart, so you can always see both in one trip 🌴 🏖 .

__label__BuenosAires,Argentina yo quiero vivir en buenos aires. 
it is cold as balls here so #traveltuesday to beautiful buenos aires, argentina. it was sunny and warm there, the beginning of spring time, when i visited. quite the opposite of the current -30 degrees here in calgary. and although it has been somewhat delayed in happening, my trip to south america is what has motivated me to finally start learning spanish. learning a new language is challenging and can become quite demotivating with its challenges, but i am ready to work hard so i can enjoy south america even more in the future. i only saw a few big cities, so next time i want to go deeper to the places where i won't have english-speaking friends to help me.

and also, argentina was my dream destination and i only ended up going because my shitty ex bailed on coming with me to colombia so i changed ny plans.

__label__Maldives imagine if you will. the sound of heavy rain puts you into a deep slumber. the weather forecast says the next day will be rainy too, so you plan to stay in and work and gaze at the rain. but in the morning, when you open one eye, bright sunlight pours in. when you step out, the air smells of rain, the beach has been washed clean, the ocean is shades of blue again, the gentle waves are caressing the sand.
.
.
so you get into your swimming gear (the sun is really strong, so that means covering up as much as possible), put on some fins, wear a snorkeling mask and wander off into the magical underwater world just off your island. you see eels, schools of big fish, scores of colourful little fish and living corals, and feel like the dimension of time doesn't apply to you anymore.
.
.
that timeless feeling, as i snorkel in the house reef off  @madi_finolhu_guesthouse 🏝
.
.
shot on @goproin ; edited with @plotagraphpro .
.
#theshootingstar #maldives #snorkeling #goproindia #lifeisbetteratthebeach

__label__Mumbai,Maharashtra a big thank you to everyone who came for the @natgeotravellerindia meetup yesterday! it was such a fun evening, talking about responsible and slow travel, hearing your stories, answering your curious questions (from hitchhiking to how to make your blog stand out), and putting a face to handles i've been tweeting / instagram chatting with for years 😇
.
.
one of my resolutions for 2017 is to fight my public speaking demons and share more of what i've learnt in my journey as a travel blogger and digital nomad. last week, i enjoyed sharing the stage with eminent travel writer dilip d'souza on a panel on travel writing at kc college, and yesterday, with @nehadara - deputy editor of nat geo, @hungryvagabond and mark hannant on what the world of travel will look like this year 🌏
.
.
next: i'll be talking about how responsible travel companies can use digital marketing to reach the right audience, along with my friend and fellow blogger @breathedreamgo - at the responsible travel summit in delhi by @outlooktraveller on 19th jan; come say hi if you're around! .
.
thanks to @dreamtravler27 & kavita peter for the photos!

__label__BrooklynBridge construction on the brooklyn bridge began in 1870 and it officially opened to the public in may of 1883. it was originally called the 'new york and brooklyn bridge' and wasn't officially given the name "brooklyn bridge" until 1915. the bridge was designated a national historic landmark in 1964. i've always loved the neo-gothic architectural style of the structure and the pointed arches that are above the passageways through the two supporting stone towers. but most importantly, because its primary engineer washington roebling -- (who took over from his father who died as a result of an accident during construction) -- designed the bridge to technically be six times stronger than it needed to be at the time, the brooklyn bridge sill stands, while most of the other bridges from that time period have long since fallen down or are simply too unsafe to use!

__label__Bali,Indonesia “you’re only as strong as your readiness to surrender.” (pico iyer) this quote has been running through my mind a lot lately. i’ve wondered - what does it truly mean to surrender?
⠀⠀⠀ ⠀
i can’t tell you i quite know the answer. but i do know this... the moments when i felt most liberated were when i let go of expectations and allowed myself to flow with the universe.
⠀⠀⠀ ⠀
we spend so much energy gripping tightly: to our fears, insecurities, and comforts. what happens when we loosen that grip and come face-to-face with what scares us, what makes us feel unworthy, what gets us uncomfortable beyond words?
⠀⠀⠀ ⠀
is it really so bad to stand there, completely vulnerable, and allow a bigger force to wash over you and cleanse you of the burden that you place on your own shoulders? to let go of the control you consistently exercise over your life, and instead surrender to your present?
⠀⠀⠀ ⠀
perhaps the secret to surrendering is giving up on what you think should happen and saying “yes” to the serendipity that comes your way. it’s accepting your darkness without judgment or trepidation. it’s asking the universe “give me what’s best for my highest good” and believing that it will provide... even when you don’t have the answers.
⠀⠀⠀ ⠀
let go, and you will find, that the transformation you seek is waiting on the other side.
⠀⠀⠀ ⠀
what does surrendering mean to you?
⠀⠀⠀ ⠀

__label__ChiangMai,Thailand it baffles me that there are some people who go on these amazing trips and don’t have one picture of themselves from the trip! okay, taking pictures of yourself is awkward, i get it.

but anybody can grab a picture from google and say they went somewhere. being in the picture is not only undeniable proof that you were there, but it conveys so much more.

your mood, your expression, and your body all change daily, and you get a chance to see how all of that looked while on a trip, to laugh or gawk at later. 😁

so embrace the moment! not only will it be the best souvenir from your trip, but it humanizes the experience for someone else.

all of a sudden, someone scrolling on their feed goes from - "oh, cool, a travel photo." to - "wait, look, my friend, in a travel photo! that could be me!" you never know who you're inspiring!

so peep the link in my bio for my best tips on how to overcome the awkwardness of photos, and unique ways to capture these precious memories. might be my favorite post this year! 😉

__label__Rome,Italy happy new year from roma where live music is playing in the piazza below our apartment, interspersed with church bells on the hour and in the distance fireworks can be seen dotting the ancient skyline. 2017 has been a year of extreme highs & lows in which i’m extraordinarily grateful to all of you who follow me. you help make it possible to do what i love for a living and that’s something i do not take for granted in a world where there’s so much pain every day. i’m choosing to focus on the good tonight, welcoming 2018 with hope. ✨ of course, a little sparkles never hurt either and my dress is courtesy of my 1 month trial of @renttherunway #rtrunlimited which i’m choosing to support because their primary mission is to help end waste in the fashion industry with a multi tiered approach to still providing women with fashionable and fun clothing. more on that soon. #myrtr👗 as for the bubbles, provided by @onehope, who were founded by eight friends with a lofty vision: to create exceptional products that inspire people to indulge while doing good — supporting them helps them support so many others, that i can’t help but want to make them part of every celebration now. through their profits, more than a million meals have been served to those who might otherwise go hungry, cancer research has been supported, trees have been planted and so much more has been accomplished to make the world a better place; all of it which you can read about via their site on the ‘impact’ page. #onehopewine 🍾 i’m not perfect but more than anything what i realized in 2017 is that i can do good with the choices i make every day, the products i buy & the businesses i support. i’m not the resolution type but i do have goals and mine for 2018 is to spend more of my life than ever before trying to spread more love than hate in every way i can. what’s your plan for this next year?

i love meeting y'all on the road, and you have no idea how much reinforcement you guys give me.

i have my days and moments (aka periods 😂) but i always know i'll have a funny snap, tweet, or ig comment waiting to cheer up my day. i love you guys so much. you have no idea! thanks for rocking my world ❤

__label__Namibia swipe across to check out 7 of my favourite pics from my namibia trip with @landrover!⚡️ this trip was so unique and incomparable to anything i've done before. it was amazing to experience the unique landscapes of namibia from the drivers seat. not only did i experience diverse parts of a new country, but i learned new off road driving skills (the best part was cruising down the beach as you may remember from my stories!)
we got off the beaten track away from the tourist crowds whilst at the same time staying in luxurious different lodges each night.
this trip was fast paced and we saw so much in just one week - the land rover experience was truly the best way to see the country and get most out of the time i had.

highlights: ~ n/a'an wildlife sanctuary where we went for a walk with 2 rescued cheetahs!
~ 'glamping' under the stars in spitzkoppe, surrounded by an insane mars like landscape.
~ quad biking in swakopmund, home to the famous dunes by the ocean.
~ sleeping in the middle of the namib desert for 2 nights where we star gazed with their in house astronomer (we rigged the camera to his telescope to get that moon shot!)
~ waking up early to walk amongst the sossusvlei dunes and the dead trees.

__label__Banff,Alberta we got a 10 minute break from the gloomy weather as the sun broke through the clouds and lit up the trees and water. a few minutes later it was gone for the rest of the day. photography is much about being in the right place at the right time, but over the years i’ve learned to appreciate the beauty in how the changing weather transforms a scene. i used to expect the best sunset and color every time i went out to shoot and the disappointment of things not living up to these expectations would ruin the experience for me. you can’t worry about things out of your control and learning to travel with lower expectations has been the key to being pleasantly surprised more often than not. a few years ago i would’ve left when i saw it was cloudy, but i’m glad i stuck around this time to see what could happen. 
shot on @sonyalpha a7riii and 16-35mm lens. #aicdoescanada

__label__Amsterdam,Netherlands [amsterdam, july 2018] much of the amsterdam canal system is the successful outcome of city planning. in the early part of the 17th century, with immigration rising, a comprehensive plan was put together, calling for four main, concentric half-circles of canals with their ends resting on the ij bay. known as the "grachtengordel", three of the canals are mostly for residential development (herengracht or ‘’patricians' canal’’; keizersgracht or ‘’emperor's canal’’; and prinsengracht or ‘’prince's canal’’), and a fourth, outer canal, the singelgracht, for purposes of defense and water management.

__label__Amsterdam,Netherlands we saw these comically tiny canta cars parked on amsterdam’ sidewalks, didn’t know what to make of them, and finally decided to search for more info on them.. it turns out there super useful and have a very specific and thoughtful purpose. .
from wikipedia: the canta is a two-seat microcar from the netherlands specifically created for disabled drivers. it is classified as a mobility aid because the width of the vehicle is only 1.10 metres, thus it may - unlike larger microcars - be used on cycle paths as well as sidewalks and footpaths; in addition a driver's license is not required.

each canta is built with the adaptations required by the customer, such as locating controls and switches on the left or right side, or all on the steering wheel. seats have a wide range of adjustment and can swivel to ease entry and exit. instead of having a driver's seat, the "ride-in canta" (inrij canta) model is designed so that a wheelchair user can enter by a ramp at the rear and drive while seated in their wheelchair. the rear of the vehicle is lowered to the ground when parked and is raised pneumatically when the engine is started.

⠀
“ashtanga” do sânscrito “ashta” – oito e “anga” – passos, é citado nos yoga sutras de patanjali, que constitui as fundações completas do ashtanga yoga, também chamada de raja yoga.⠀

__label__NewYork,NewYork спрашивали про медицину в сша👩‍⚕️
⠀
общеизвестные факты:
🔹дорого
🔹лучше не болеть
🔹иметь страховку, но все равно лучше не болеть😁
⠀
конечно, если вы работаете в престижной компании, которая предоставляет вам соц.пакет и хорошую медицинскую страховку, то переживать не о чем. если компания страховку не предоставляет, придётся за неё платить самому. цены разные, в зависимости, что покрывает страховка💰к примеру, страховка на всю семью обходится в $400, $300 оплачивает работодатель и $100 платите сами.
⠀
еще один вариант при доходе ниже минимума - бесплатная государственная страховка medicaid. программа медикейд доступна для инвалидов и малообеспеченных, детей и беременных женщин, а также для людей старше 65 лет.
кстати, если у детей медикейд, им положена бесплатная чистка зубов два раза в год, лечение, но услуги ортодонта и брекеты страховкой уже не покроются. большая часть русскоговорящих иммигрантов, что я встречала, пользовались медикейд.
⠀
а что делать тем, у кого никакой страховки нет. придётся выложить круглую сумму за поход к врачу. хорошо тем, кто живет в нью-йорке. там много русских аптек, в которых продаются практически все наши лекарства. я покупала себе и кире противовирусные без проблем, рецепт нужен только для антибиотиков.
⠀
в целом, медицинскую страховку в америке лучше иметь.
⠀

__label__Budapest,Hungary budapest is a city on either side of the majestic danube: buda, with its romantic streets and alleyways, and pest, an effervescent cultural centre. 
divided in two by the danube, the city is made up of buda on one side: with ottoman-era thermal baths at the foot of the spectacular gellért hill, the royal palace and matthias church, it radiates calm and peace. one the other side lies pest, vibrant and lively, with its slew of museums rich in cultural and historical treasures, extraordinary secessionist architecture, its majestic parliament building considered as one of the most magnificent in the world, saint stephen’s basilica surrounded by pedestrian streets, and its entirely renovated jewish quarter and palace district. the budapest eye is city's new attraction which came into operation since 2015. this 65 meters high is one of the largest mobile ferry wheel in europe and in the evening it offers a magical ride full of colors and stunning landscapes of budapest.
i will keep putting more pics from budapest soon..!!

__label__Mexico i was out shooting stars at this waterfall in chiapas. then, about an hour before sunrise a blanket of fog swam into the spot i was shooting.
i almost went back to bed, assuming sunrise would be a wash. 
but, i stuck it out just in case. 
then, about 15 minutes before the sun popped up, the fog rolled away leaving an eerily beautiful scene of lingering fog, sillouetted trees, and dancing waters.

__label__Venezia,Italia so called the “canalazzo“, is the most important water way of venice, about 3800 meters long, it splits the city in two sides.

venice from above looks like a big fish, not bad for a city on the sea! the grand canal it's like a thick dark line that creates a kind of "big s" inside the fish.

by each side there are many magnificent buildings (from a period dated between xii and xvii century) that testify the richness and beauty of the art of the “serenissima“ republic!

hawaii is so beautiful that i almost feel like it’s easy to keep things superficial when showing it to visitors. waterfalls. white sand beaches. this trip was very much not that. instead of just seeing the volcano, we got to do things like learn about the science behind it while flying with renown hawaii volcanologist jack lockwood, see a hula as led by lifetime practitioner kumu hula laakea perry, pick our own fruits to be used in a dinner with chuck, the owner of ono organic farms.💛
-
@fshualalai, @fslanai, @fsoahu, @fsmaui thank you for not only showing us the best and most beautiful of each island, but for also making this hawaii girl very proud of the way you’re presenting and seeking out local organizations and individuals to share, what i view, as the more meaningful part of hawaii.
-
to check out or book our exact itinerary use the swipe up link in my story :) #hawaiibyfs

__label__Warsaw,Poland 1. this week i'll be sharing my stories and my favorite destinations, so you'll have a chance to get to know me a bit better 😊 
i was born and raised in #warsaw, #poland - where this photo was taken (polish people: do you know this spot?😉). * my parents both used to travel internationally, but not with me (that, i had to do on my own for my own money😝) and every vacation they were taking me to the same spots in poland every year: sea in the summer and mountains in the winter. not too exciting 😂
* i completed my first degree in poland (because it's free and university actually paid me for having good grades 😋). fun fact: i actually graduated in 1,5 year (gonna explain how can you do this in a big blog post soon). * i've had to learn english and other languages, take on random jobs and save all my money to move abroad right after. * i took half a year off to do a mini-gap year. i visited thailand, canada, tunisia, israel, egypt, moved to nyc for a bit, visited california and nevada - all of it before moving to london for my master's degree. my trip showed me that while i loved traveling, doing it full-time without a home base wasn't my thing as i had too many other things and interests i wanted to do as well. this is how my 'travel from a home-base' style was born 😉
**

__label__Istanbul,Turkey the most beautiful sea:  hasn't been crossed yet.
the most beautiful child:  hasn't grown up yet.
our most beautiful days:  we haven't seen yet.
and the most beautiful words i wanted to tell you, i haven't said yet. (nazim hikmet) 🥀 
cамое лучшее море:  то, где еще не плавал.самый лучший ребенок:  тот, что еще не вырос. самые лучшие дни нашей жизни:  те, что еще не прожиты. и самое прекрасное из сказанных тебе слов:  то, что я еще скажу. (nazım hikmet) 🌷

il più bello dei mari
è quello che non abbiamo navigato.
il più bello dei nostri figli
non è ancora cresciuto.
i più belli dei nostri giorni
non li abbiamo ancora vissuti.
e quello
che vorrei dirti di più bello
non te l'ho ancora detto (nazım hikmet) 🥀 la plus belle mer: n'a pas encore été traversée.
le plus bel enfant: n'a pas encore grandi.
nos plus beaux jours: nous n'avons pas encore vu. et les plus belles paroles que je voulais te dire, je ne l'ai pas encore dit. (nazim hikmet) 🥀el más bello de los mares
es aquel que no hemos visto.
la más linda criatura
todavía no ha nacido.
nuestros días más hermosos
aún no los hemos vivido.
y lo mejor de todo aquello que tengo que decirte
todavía no lo he dicho (nazım hikmet) (originally turkish poem) 🥀en güzel deniz:henüz gidilmemiş olanıdır,
en güzel çocuk: henüz büyümedi.
en güzel günlerimiz: henüz yaşamadiklarımız,

__label__Lofoten this beach changed my life. amidst losing all feeling in my toes & fingers i had never actually felt more deeply than in this moment years ago. i learned valuable lessons about the important of risk, and the joys of enduring the cold on that beach. it's been a few years but i always knew i would return at some point. this saturday i fly back to norway for a quick trip to revisit some of these places that inspired me so long ago. it was even the basis for my ted talk & a big section of the memoir i've been writing.

__label__ChiangMai,Thailand i guess i’m a few years too late to doing the digital nomad thing in chiang mai... but i’m glad i finally decided to give it a try! .
.
this is our incredible abode amid a private forest, on the outskirts of chiang mai - for the next month or so. just a 10 minute scooter ride into the mountains, with soulful buddhist temples and cycling trails through dense forests. and on the other side of those mountains lies burma. .
.
the city of chiang mai is a vegan haven, but it’s a bit too busy for me. luckily we don’t have to venture that far to seek vegan food; within a 5 km radius, we’ve already found a ton of delicious, organic, healthy, vegan-friendly, wallet-friendly thai and international places to eat. plus it’s such a luxury to have a nice kitchen to cook in again.
.
.
i’ve been to northern thailand a bunch of times, but always thought chiang mai would be too commercial / touristy / overrun for my liking. i’m glad i finally decided to give it a try, even if a few years too late 😉
.
.
ps: how did i find such an incredible @airbnb? see the link in my bio for all the hacks and tricks i’ve learnt over the years. .

__label__Vienna,Austria 31 декабря 2017 г. удивило, что в новогоднюю ночь в вене шампанское, глинтвейн и прочие алкогольные и безалкогольные напитки продают на улицах вместе со стеклянными фужерами и керамическими кружками - расписными, с пожеланиями счастливого нового года, в форме поросят и дедов морозов. и праздник отметишь, и сувениры домой привезешь. согласитесь, так вкус праздника ощущать гораздо приятнее. а бумажные и пластиковые стаканчики, которые практикуют в москве на массовых мероприятиях, в целях безопасности, не способны издавать волшебный звон. кстати, о безопасности, в вене всё было спокойно: никто посуду об головы друг друга не бил.

⠀⠀⠀ ⠀
opportunities will drop from the sky. you’ll meet the right people. you’ll ask questions, and your surroundings will give you the answers. these “coincidences” will bring you closer to your goals, and they will happen because you took a step forward.

__label__India happy 70th independence day, india 🇮🇳
.
.
70 years on, here's the irony of our country: we drive the world's fanciest cars but don't see eye to eye with the man trying to make a living in the sultry heat or biting cold. we eat gourmet international food but bargain with the vegetable seller who walks for miles to get fresh produce. we have world class kitchens and culinary gadgets, but don't eat on the same table as the people we employ to cook in them. we've overrun our towns with ugly concrete construction but we only need to go to the outskirts to see dancing peacocks and running chinkara. the entrance to opulent havelis owned by millionaires is lined with open, stinking sewers. we say our religions forbid cruelty towards animals, yet we guiltlessly devour their milk and meat. we complain of racism abroad, but are racist towards our own countrymen...
.
.
i could go on, but here's the thing. we're some of the luckiest people on earth to be born amid the incredible natural beauty, wildlife and cultural diversity of india. 70 years on, can we stop the faux patriotism and pledge today to treat our fellow humans and animals and nature like they belong to this country - and this earth - too? 🤔
.
.
collab with @searchingsid ; his photo, my words.
.
.
#theshootingstar #independencedayindia #incredibleindia #indiatravel #indialove

__label__Bali,Indonesia let's talk parental support. who here has parents that are furious with your career path or would be extremely disappointed if you chased your dreams?

i'm always very transparent about my nigerian upbringing and its strict guidelines for our lives - where you're either a doctor, a lawyer, or a disappointment.

it's both a cultural and generational disconnect when your elders hold onto very traditional ideas of what defines success.

they also want nothing more than for their kids to be financially set and afforded opportunities they never had, so they hold the practice of medicine or law as the holy grail of adulthood.

other things they also admire, masters degrees, marriage in your 20s, kids in your 30s, buying them a car in your 40s, retiring them in your 50s, and you better not gain a single pound or acquire acne from the stress of unrealistic expectations in the process 🙃

over the last 5 years, my mom has lectured me several times about how this "hobby" of blogging is useless and will never get me anywhere, and in typical aries fashion i used that to fuel me even more.

obviously we all want nothing more than to make our parents proud (my dad passed away two weeks before my first international trip in 2012 but he was 10x stricter than my mother, so just imagine), but there will come a sad day in life where both your parents will no longer be around.

and if you spent all those years doing nothing but trying to make them happy, what will you be left with when they're gone?

all of a sudden, that pride that you made them happy is short-lived when you go to sleep every night hating your life and wishing you could have pursued what you really loved.

at the end of the day, there are two people who i'm aiming to please. the woman in the mirror and the man upstairs.

anybody after that is just a bonus.

but your happiness isn't just defined by a career path. it's a life-long journey that your passions and sense of fulfillment in this world shapes daily.

the saddest life isn't the one who dies prematurely. it's the one who lived a full and long life for the approval of someone else.

your happiness is always worth pursuing. i hope this spoke to someone today ❤

__label__Antarctica i remember the days when all of these and all of what i have now were still dreams and aspirations ✨❤️
- - -
exactly a year ago, i was on an expedition to antarctica as i mingled with millions of penguins, learned loads about our environment together with scientists, (and more!). and then, a few months later, i got the chance to visit africa which made me hit my biggest travel goal of visiting all 7 continents of the world! 🤩
- - -
if you told me 10 years ago that i would be able to do this all in my 20s then you bet that i’ll be laughing at you, not believing a word — and yet look at where i am now. ✨ i don’t want to get all sappy but i already am now lol. so i just want to say how i’m humbled by it all and i will forever be thankful for you guys because you’re a part of how i was able to pursue my dreams and passion.
- - -
today, as i look back, i gotta say that i’m overwhelmed (in a good way). i’ve been traveling every month for the past 3 years and i think it’s time that i sit back and slow down a bit. therefore, i made it a point to not travel until june of next year — but this isn’t going to be a bad thing because this will enable me to churn out more content for you guys as i go through all my backlog lol. ✌🏻 (but yeah, i think this aim won’t last long because i might be itching to take on a travel offer if it’s interesting enough— but i’ll be trying my best). so i guess what i’m trying to say is: thank you for sticking around and i hope you’d enjoy more of my content in the next year!
- - -

__label__Venezia,Italia venetian red is still a thing. made from ferric oxide it is also known as sinopia, because the best pigments came from sinop in turkey. it was mixed with lime white to create skin tones, and along with ultramarine was a major element of renaissance paintings. it was also the colour of british army jackets (the redcoats), until it was replaced by khaki in the 1890s #venice #everydaybeauty #lpinitaly

__label__Zanzibar,Tanzania there comes a moment in your life when you forget who you are and where you come from. when all that matters is where you are. you let your hair and inhibitions down, you feel the wind on your skin and the soft sand on your feet, you sing to the sea and drown your thoughts in the gentle waves, you run and spin like no one's watching. it doesn't matter that your bank balance has dropped to the scary 4 digits and you have no idea where you'll go from here. it doesn't even matter that in another world, life's bigger questions sit unsolved at your desk. all that matters is that you're here, you're living this moment. you are being you. 
that kind of moment in zanzibar 😍

and you, when was the last time you had a moment like that?

__label__Washington we stopped at a ranger station to acquire a backcountry permit and were reminded to camp only on dirt and rocks, absolutely no foliage. when we arrived, we scoured the area and found just one obvious campsite. all dirt, lined with rocks. but even then, we dropped our packs and continued to roam around in search for additional options. we brought the required bear canister and blue bags for human waste. we did all the things, and yet... i haven’t wanted to post this image because i’m confident the first thing that will come to some folks minds is “that’s not 200 feet from the water!” and that wouldn’t be an inaccurate statement - i’m pretty sure it wasn’t. it’s definitely farther from the water than this image makes it appear... but that’s the fun and sometimes difficult part about photography.
.
lnt are guidelines that all of us wilderness lovers should know and practice. but the stars don’t always align where you can check all the boxes. so do the best you can. good campsites are found, not made. clearing out an area, farther from the water would have done far more damage to this fragile place than taking up residency in an already existing spot closer to the lake.
.
but the point of this post is... there’s a lot of flack these days, people and accounts being reported and blasted for outdoor ethics or lack thereof. i’m in full support of respecting and protecting the environment, following the rules, and putting those things above myself and my images... but it’s good to remember this; a simple image doesn’t usually tell a complete story.

__label__Philippines крик души, а может и желудка🍍🥑
⠀
филиппины - первая страна в моей жизни, в которой я не могу есть местную кухню. еда очень жирная и сладкая! сахар добавляют даже в обычные магазинные сосиски.
⠀
местные жители совершенно не едят фрукты (хотя живут в тропиках) и морепродукты. говядину на островах встретишь редко (стоит она космических денег), а вот свинину филиппинцы просто обожают. они едят ее прямо с кожей и жиром😨. любимый способ приготовления - фритюр, в котором масло не менялось годами (макдональдс и kfc нервно курят в сторонке). пончики, котлетки, кусочки овощей и даже фруктов - все это окунают в кипящее масло, а затем тоннами поглощают в уличных кафе.
⠀
а еще филиппинцы практические не пьют молоко и не едят молочные продукты. молоко в тетрапаках, конечно, продается в магазинах, но пить его практически невозможно. свежее молоко можно достать только на молочной ферме. в крупных супермаркетах стоят холодильники с козьим молоком (230 руб. за литр). йогурты - вообще удовольствие для туристов, маленький стаканчик стоит как полкило кальмаров или как полноценный обед на одного в уличном кафе.
⠀
если вы вегетарианец (как и я), вам придется туго в этой стране. в местных кафе /ресторанах довольно скудный выбор вегетарианских блюд. на рынках и в супермаркетах ситуация обстоит не лучше: пластиковые помидоры, безвкусные огурцы, дорогущие морковка и картофель. даже не представляю, чем здесь питаются веганы. наверное, сидят на рисе и манго. кстати, манго тут довольно дорогое (от 100 - 160 руб. за кило). вот так и живем🙃 ⠀⠀
⠀

__label__Iceland well iceland... you've been amazing, but this hike was easily one of the highlights of the trip. @chelseakauai and i met @joe_shutter and @frankframesthings on our third day, by chance, while finishing up lunch and we got to chatting... and a couple days later, we met up again and they took us out to this incredibly special place.
.
this trip was wonderful because we never really had a set agenda. sure, we had an idea of some of the places we wanted to go and the things we wanted to see, but the best memories weren't created at those iconic icelandic viewpoints that everyone has seen a thousand times. they happened when we chose to be spontaneous. i saw such a tiny fraction of what iceland had to offer, but i definitely experienced enough to know that i want to come back and experience so much more.
.
.

__label__Iceland this is another favorite photo of me. i was actually pretty terrified to get close to this icelandic horse which is ironic because horses were my favorite animal growing up. i have a weird fear when it comes to touching or being near horses. to me they feel like giants that could bite my entire hand off and eat it like a delicious apple(yes i’m being dramatic). but when i was researching iceland the horses were a huge deal and i knew that when i arrived i needed to see one in person, which wasn’t too hard because they were everywhere. when the time came to be face to face with one i was nervous but this specific black horse in this photo walked up to me with no fear and i think i was inspired by its bravery because without skepticism as soon as the horse was inches away from me i placed my hand on its face and my sister snapped this photo. it was a quick moment but a moment that’ll last forever. #iceland
