__label__Bangkok,Thailand flying dong at wat saket🎯
locals prefer to travel by canal ferry as it’s faster (bangkok traffic can be too much) and cheaper so i gotta try this mode of transportation here in canals and i love it! no traffic jams, see more locals and also it’s off the typical tourist trail. .
wat saket or the golden mount temple built on an artificial hill is not a popular with buddhists and tourists. the base of wat saket is an unusual cemetery built covered in vines and overgrown trees, it emits a rather spooky out-of-era vibe. perhaps this is because in the late 18th century, wat saket served as the capital's crematorium and the dumping ground for some 60,000 plague victims. approaching the top of the hill, you will be welcomed by a wall of bells and panoramas of historic bangkok.
.
i didn’t see any dog 🐕 in bangkok so i gave in to cat love attack and then relaxing at hotel pool with city view.

__label__Istanbul,Turkey made it to istanbul on what might've been one of the craziest adventures yet - riding through bulgaria by train.

the conditions were so bad, our train broke down every few minutes. it took us 4 hours to go 25 miles 😣😭. but that didn't stop us from hanging our heads out the window while drinking romanian beer, admiring bulgaria's countryside views in our 100-seat cabin split amongst all 8 of us, haha.

then we finally reach the border and the border patrol take my passport and when i come outside, they're saying things and pointing my direction. i laugh and ask, "what'd i do?" and they say, "haha, ez bee-cos ju luk like seh-veena vee-liums". (serena williams) #iwish 😂😂😂

__label__Utah utah has some amazing looking badlands / desert scenes! willie, david and i are heading back to the desert this week, so it got me thinking about this trip to southern utah. it’s a neat area because it has the giant factory butte, beautiful badlands, stunning mesas and plateaus, and crazy desert landscape. there’s a lot to photograph in this area and i can see why we randomly ran into a few of our photographer friends.
.
on our last morning here we woke up early and traveled up a dirt road in search of a view that would look on the wall of factory butte. we found a set of rocks that we could climb onto that would give us a little bit of an elevated view onto the butte.
.
i loved the lines that come down from the wall of factory butte. it makes you wonder how this crazy landscape formed. how does it not all fall down? how were those crazy shapes made, interlocking into each other? #badlands #utah #desert #sunrise #factory #plateau 📷🌉🏕🌇📸🏞

__label__Greece i used to think that we had one soul mate that we would marry, spend the rest of our lives, and live happily ever after with.
⠀⠀⠀ ⠀
perhaps that's true for a select few, but i've found that in today's society, this view on love is not realistic.
⠀⠀⠀ ⠀
you can spend a lifetime with someone and reach a point where you don't even feel like you know them, or you can spend 24 hours and understand that person in ways that no one else could before that moment.
⠀⠀⠀ ⠀
sometimes, two souls just recognize each other. when that synchronicity happens, our hearts crack open, we are pushed to challenge ourselves and our expectations, and we grow further into our ideal selves.
⠀⠀⠀ ⠀
i've begun to measure my love not by time or space, but rather by intensity. it's not a matter of "will i marry this person" anymore. instead, it's "can i love with an open heart in this time we have together?"
⠀⠀⠀ ⠀
my travels have taught me that nothing is forever. but just because not all love is permanent, it doesn't mean it cannot be lived fully while it's there.
⠀⠀⠀ ⠀
love with an open heart, bask in the incredible intimacy of human connection, and do not be afraid to let go when that love has run its course.
⠀⠀⠀ ⠀
when it's meant to be, it will return.
⠀⠀⠀ ⠀
when it's not, it will make you stronger.
⠀⠀⠀ ⠀
love like it's forever. each moment holds with it a piece of eternity.
⠀⠀⠀ ⠀

❀
woƞԁεrιαηd
.
people always desire to see beautiful places and experience wonderlands. 👀 in the reality, not all the experiences are perfect: we see a wonderful winter landscape with pretty houses, but dante and me were freezing at the moment, our hands were hurting because of the cold, and my socks were already wet because i didn't bring waterproof boots ❄️👢 but wonderland for us is the feeling in our hearts when we visit beautiful places: the excitement, the joy, the love. our hearts can feel so many things at the same time, let's enjoy the wonderland in ourselves ❤️ spanish:

la gente siempre desea ver lugares hermosos y experimentar los paraisos. 👀 en la realidad, no todas las experiencias son perfectas: vemos el maravilloso escenario con las bellas casas, pero dante y yo nos congelabamos en ese momento, nuestras manos dolian por el frio y mis calcetines estaban mojados porque no lleve botas especiales ❄👢pero el paraiso para nosotros es el sentir en nuestros corazones cuando vamos a esos lugares: la emocion, la alegria, el amor. nuestros corazones pueden sentir tantas cosas al mismo tiempo, disfrutemos del paraiso en nosotros mismos ❤️
❀
what is wonderland for you? share your thoughts with us in the comments 🌿

__label__Barcelona,Spain feliç sant jordi! el día de los amantes! ❤🌷 today is the "valentine's day" of catalunya, or the day of lovers, as it's sometimes called. a day full of roses, romance, and books.

the men give their lady a rose, and the ladies give their man a book. if you pass by the elementary schools, you'll even see the little kids dressed up as mini warriors and the girls as mini princesses (but i mainly saw elsa costumes 😂). the timeless fairytale of the patron saint george playing the knight in shining armour, rescuing a damsel in distress from a dragon is about as cliché as it gets, but that symbolism of love, chivalry, and heroism is what this day is about. so brb, just can't evening right now. 😍

__label__UnitedStates whether we like to admit it or not .. if you're holding a cell phone in your hand and scrolling through photos & stories of places you want to go and experience you can consider yourself privileged. i know i do. the truth is much of that privilege is built upon the sacrifice of others... many who came long before us.
.

as we take a second to remember what memorial day actually means, a time to honor those who have sacrificed their lives while serving, we should remember what this day is truly about. ( ps it's not shopping ) stay safe out there 🇺🇸🙏🏼✌🏼

__label__Goa,India that feeling of freedom, driving around goa in the monsoons. the rice paddies swaying on either side. the rustling of palm trees. men on bicycles selling poi and pao from house to house. women hanging outside their homes in their nighties. going out in flip flops with friends. peeping into old abandoned portuguese style houses. a light drizzle on our faces, a nip in the air, warm sunlight pouring through the dark clouds. that feeling of being in goa 😍
.
.

.

__label__HongKong the more i travel, the more i realize there are countless places i could call home. i know it might be cheesy to post this while wearing a $20 kimono i bought at the night market but it’s true. every day i feel less tied to one location and more open to different cultures, foods and people. 
right now @whatthechic @melissa @aleporte and i are exploring #southkorea and this is definitely a city i want to live in for a month or so. it has so much to offer and the food has been mind blowing. 
i highly recommend you take the opportunity to do a school exchange, work placement or gap year abroad to see another destination and to become a local there. it will change your perspective of the world for the better.

__label__London,UnitedKingdom ever wondered what these little huts are? they’re cabman’s shelters! little huts for horse and carriage drivers to stop and get a snack and for their horses to take a break back in the day when uber didn’t exist. there are 13 left in london and they’re all grade 2 listed so can’t be taken down. only licensed cabbies can go in them so they’re like a little private club in the middle of the street.

__label__LaJolla,California if you ever feel alone, if you feel deserted or as if the whole world around you is crumbling in front of your eyes, remember this: allow yourself to find peace from within, for all things in nature change and grow. changing seasons ignite new paths for us to walk. fresh winds will blow away the dust that once clouded your vision. as the clouds clear to ignite the light in the sky it’ll illuminate that we are never really alone in this universe. for we all have been gifted this opportunity to experience the joy of life together. albeit in different unique ways but that’s what makes it even more special! 
i hope the new year brings you all the joy and light you desire in your life ✌🏼i’m grateful for all the connections i’ve made over this past year, the adventures i’ve had and the beautiful places i’ve been. each moment has been special (the good and the bad) which have all taught me invaluable lessons. happy new year, may your lives be blessed with love & light ✨🤙🏻

__label__Prague,CzechRepublic i have fond memories of this grainy old shot of prague in 2007.
this was the first time i ventured into eastern europe, and i was pretty excited! it was a rough start - crossing by bus from germany into czech republic, i was the only one pulled off the vehicle for a little extra attention. 
the authorities thought i had overstayed in the schengen zone, because i was never stamped coming through the tunnel from u.k to france, thus i only had an entry stamp from the u.k. i eventually managed to convince them otherwise, thankfully. i never have the best relationships with border authorities, but more stories on that will come soon! 
the funny thing about this situation is my best friend who was traveling with me throughout 2007 had exactly the same stamps (or lack of) as me...and he remained comfortably warm inside the bus! 😆🛃

__label__MexicoCity,Mexico i think every time you visit a new place you meet a different side of yourself, and if you like the direction it makes you grow, you can’t help but come back for water. mexico city has always brought out the lightest version of me; the one who laughs at nothing and doesn’t care about her tangled hair or mangled spanish. when i say i miss a place, of course i miss its sounds and culture and food and people. but i think what i miss most is the girl i left there, a me who is deserving of nostalgia, or even better, a concerted effort to pull her out of my memories and into the present. i’m sure i’ll be back here soon– it’s hard to resist a place that brings out all your favorite traits in complementary measures. but until then, to this girl; to the people she met, to the places she went, and to the tacos she photographed.

__label__Barcelona,Spain third stop: 📍 barcelona, spain
** part 1

1. the arco de triunfo de barcelona - constructed as the main gateway to barcelona’s world fair in 1888
2. el born cultural centre - once a market, now displays 1700s excavated ruins 
3. the shortest street in barcelona, with only one street number within it
4. many of the shops, cafés and restaurants in the city have these plaques on the ground in front of them. they commemorate the long history of these vendors; hence, every 100 years a date stamp is added to the plaque
5. plaça reial (or royal plaza) is the only “spanish” square in the city as  barcelona is within the catalan region of spain. well-known catalan architect, antoni gaudí designed the square’s lampposts
6. la rambla - long tourist boulevard in barcelona that stretches 1.2km with food and souvenir vendors 
7. mercat de la boqueria - a large public market in barcelona selling a variety of goods from fruit to seafood to sweets and everything in between
8. one of the many beautifully designed buildings by antoni gaudí
9. casa batlló - another building architecturally created by gaudí; however, it is created under construction to restore parts of the structure
10. la sagrada familia - a large roman catholic church designed by gaudí that has been under construction for more than 135 years and is expected to be completed in 2026. here, laura (@laurasansc) and i hold my signed dutch flag from our exchange

__label__Madrid,Spain day 202:
•madrid•
way more chilled out than barcelona, spotlessly clean and chocked full of parks and gorgeous little flower shops like this one, we enjoyed our day trip to madrid immensely! .
after an exhausting day with the pack in toledo yesterday we managed to find an incredibly safe place to park in central madrid and left the dogs for a few hours whilst alex and i had date day in the city. we haven’t ever left the dogs before and it didn’t feel very nice so we are unlikely to do it again but our quiet, relaxing walk arm in arm through the streets made us realise how much easier and less stressful this trip would have been if we didn’t already have merlin and rupert. that being said we would never have taken this road trip if they weren’t in our lives and would have instead gone backpacking so pluses and minuses!
.
our stroll took us past the absolutely ginormous royal palace that has over 3500 rooms (although only a stingy 15 for tourists) and dominates the skyline as it sprawls along the acropolis. we then had some tasty tapas in the historic mercado de san miguel including olives, paella and potatoes skewers! .
by now we were missing our family so we walked back via the charming plaza mayor to find monday where we parked her in a stunning park near the templo de debod which was a gift to spain from egypt! .
after lots of happy greetings from our boys (and now girl) i whipped up some mango pineapple smoothies and we all walked up to the park and sat on a bench for a couple of hours drinking our smoothies, people watching and listening to a saxophonist who suddenly appeared as the sun was beginning to set. it was pure magic. .
tomorrow we wake early and have a driving day all the way up to bilbao, stopping on the way for water etc. we have a few days exploring the area including san sebastián before we head into france. we don’t want to go to early, we are still anxiously evading the cold. it’s not going to last though, that much we know! .
.
.
.
.

__label__Havana,Cuba one of the coolest things about cuba is that every car is essentially a taxi driver. hitchhiking is also really common/easy here for that exact reason.

these are called collective taxis (taxi colectivos) and for less than $1, you can get yourself a few blocks/minutes down the road.

of course these cars are dated, but they still run like whistles, built for fashion and function.

but it definitely took me a few days to stop reaching for seat belts that were never there, lol.

one time when i reached over for the seat belt while in the front of a taxi, he laughed and said, "this is cuba... no belt, no problem!" jesus take the wheel. #literally

__label__Hawaii i used to really fight against visiting a place more than once. there are just so many beautiful places to see. but i’ve recently changed my attitude. as i grow, my priorities change, and so do the ways that i experience a place. no matter how many times i return to a location, there’s always something new to take away, not only about the location, but about myself. and i love the journey of peeling back the many layers of a destination until you finally get to feel the pulse of its beating heart.
-
photo: @everchanginghorizon

__label__Bali,Indonesia i’m going to tell you a secret.
⠀⠀⠀ ⠀
i have these three personal stories. whenever someone gets close and wants to know more about me, i whip them out, so they can feel satisfied by my openness and vulnerability. so they can stop asking for more.
⠀⠀⠀ ⠀
but… i’ve told these stories a million times. i don’t feel the pain anymore. i could have just as easily told you what i had for lunch.
⠀⠀⠀ ⠀
you see, to get up close and personal with somebody… it’s terrifying.
⠀⠀⠀ ⠀
it means exposing myself. my vulnerabilities. my fears. my insecurities.
⠀⠀⠀ ⠀
so i package my “vulnerability” stories, i hand one out to whoever gets too close, and secretly hope it’s enough for them.
⠀⠀⠀ ⠀
but for the people who truly understand me, it’s not enough.
⠀⠀⠀ ⠀
because they know that it’s not the moments that i pose or prepare for that define me. it’s those in between.
⠀⠀⠀ ⠀
my vulnerability still hides between the lines of my stories, suspended in the off-guard moments when i think that no one is watching.
⠀⠀⠀ ⠀
this is my weakness. and i share it with you, so that it may see the light.
⠀⠀⠀ ⠀
photo by my favorite photographer @cristopher_benitah. thank you, my friend, for seeing in me what i don’t always see in myself 🙏🏼.

__label__BuenosAires,Argentina day 13 - post 1 - december 2018
•
walking through this metropolitan city feels like walking through a dream land in which paris and new york had a baby that they left on the south american continent. the culture is spanish, the buildings are french, the food is italian (when you’re not eating massive amounts of steak) and the people are just a little bit ny snarky. you’ll spot the locals (porteños) because they all walk around with mate cups and thermoses for their daily dose of caffeine. in a world of strange paradoxes- like needing reservations for dinner a week in advance for literally any place, or the inability to stand at a bar when all seats are taken, this city finds ways to boggle your mind both in a phenomenal way and in one that may make you want to scream all at the same time 🤯🥰

__label__Stockholm,Sweden i like to be proven wrong. maybe that’s why travel has become such a fundamental part of me: wherever i go, my preconceptions are challenged. i push myself to look beyond what i thought was true.
⠀⠀⠀ ⠀
that’s what happened in sweden.
⠀⠀⠀ ⠀
i was pretty “meh” before coming here, mostly because i had heard that the swedes were:
⠀⠀⠀ ⠀
- extremely reserved
- super shy
- conflict avoidant
- only themselves when they got drunk
⠀⠀⠀ ⠀
ok, there was some truth behind these warnings (especially the last one haha) but what i found - pretty much right away - was so much more.
⠀⠀⠀ ⠀
once i cracked through their initial façade, the swedes i interacted with had a soft, gentle kindness. as a collective, i found them to be independent, very open-minded, with a good sense of humor (witty af), and extremely calm. if i had to describe them in one word, it would be: unflappable.
⠀⠀⠀ ⠀
as a non-swedish friend living in stockholm told me: "swedes are like a frozen lake. once you crack the top layer, you'll see there is so much depth and beauty inside."
⠀⠀⠀ ⠀
i couldn’t have found this to be more true. in other words…
⠀⠀⠀ ⠀
i love you, sweden!
⠀⠀⠀ ⠀

__label__ChiangMai,Thailand i don't own anything that comes even remotely close to equaling the price of my freedom to live where and how i please.

i struggled so much to get to this point, especially as an adolescent. and if i knew those phases were only preparing me for this, i'd do it all over again in a heartbeat.

you might be going through a troubling phase in life, and wondering if you'll ever see a light at the end of the tunnel.

and once you do, you realize it's just an oncoming train 😭🚈 but trust me when i say the best way to build the mental capacity to develop the better part of your being, is to go through these trials and hardships. hate them but embrace them. we all have our struggles no matter where we are in life.

we also all have the same 24 hours in a day to decide to do something about them. let the thought of your breakthrough be the reason you break through.

there's a better you on the other side, i promise. not sure who i wrote this for, but something was tugging on my heart to share. ❤

__label__Kauai i am fascinated by the all the wild in this world. by nature, which never ceases to be alternately beautiful, haunting and humbling.
-
the historic flooding the last two days on kaua’i has been unlike anything i’ve seen or experienced. a few thoughts from my very scattered mind: 
1. thank you so so much to everyone who has donated, shared, and sent well wishes to the community here. kauai is obviously very special to me and it seems it is to a great many of you too.💙
2. i know the damage assessment is just getting started and if there are opportunities to assist (on island or from afar) i’ll let you know. or please inform me of any projects on island i can help with
3. i am so insanely proud to be from this island!! even with roads washed away and so many homes flooded, i know everything will be ok. because i learned a long time ago people here, perhaps people everywhere...we aren’t good at sitting still when there’s work to be done. the beauty i see in this island is as much in the dna of the people as it is in its outward appearance. my love to your warrior souls, creative minds, helping hands :) #home #kauai

i guess now is also a good time to announce that i have my antarctica video up on youtube and alllllll the posts on my blog! check mi stories for links!

__label__Copenhagen my time in denmark really got me thinking about the meaning of “contentment.”
⠀⠀⠀ ⠀
it’s a word that’s thrown around a lot here. the danes are all about living in the present, being satisfied with what they have (after all, “it could be worse”), and have a sort of “if it’s not broken, don’t fix it” mentality.
⠀⠀⠀ ⠀
clearly something is working for them - they’re one of the happiest countries in the world, and the societal structure they’ve built for themselves works.
⠀⠀⠀ ⠀
while i find this general contentment with life quite beautiful, i also have qualms with it. it may not be broken, but what if there’s something that works even better? and if you are used to everything working smoothly, do you get too comfortable in that security and certainty? what if you’re truly unhappy and want to make a change in your life - will that contentment transform into complacency and fear of uncertainty? ⠀⠀⠀ ⠀
i am not saying that one mindset is better than the other - it’s incredible to witness a society who collectively feels so content. personally, i always strive for more and find it hard to feel satisfied with “the way things are” for too long. i want to learn the art of contentment so i can happily slow down, but i also fear getting “stuck” in it and not making the transformations i wish to see in my life.
⠀⠀⠀ ⠀
what do you guys think? where is the line between contentment and complacency?
⠀⠀⠀ ⠀

__label__AngkorWat,SiemReap,Cambodia / храм, который поглотили джунгли /
⠀
закрутился в потоке событий, и совсем забыл поделиться с вами нереально крутыми местами в камбодже 😱, буду исправлять)
⠀
это, наверное, самый эпичный храм, который мы успели посетить в ангкоре. я просто не верил своим глазам.😱 гиганские деревья буквально поглощают древние сооружения.
⠀
та пром (ta prohm), также известный в народе как «храм анджелины джоли» - это визитная карточка ангкора. именно здесь проходили съемки 🎥 «лара крофт: расхитительница гробниц». анджелина джоли бодро прыгала по древним развалинам, опутанным корнями деревьев, и отстреливалась от негодяев. после выхода фильма туристы хлынули в ангкор рекой. каждый хотел своим глазами увидеть это чудо света.😱
⠀
освободить строения от деревьев не представлялось возможным, храм просто-напросто рассыпался бы на части😔. именно поэтому археологи решили оставить все как есть и были правы, ведь гигантские деревья🌳🌳🌳, обнимающие древние руины, — зрелище, способное заставить ахнуть даже человека, который видел все.😦😦😦
⠀
на мой взгляд, решение уступить та пром джунглям абсолютно гениально. а вы как думаете? впечатляет?)
⠀
⠀

__label__Milan,Italy these are my hosts in #milan: federico (@effescuolo), michael (@michaelcastorino), giuseppe (@gc53), and the pup is chuck. respectively, their dreams are to live doing what he loves in a tranquil place; to become a successful actor; and to see his father again; (i don't speak dog, but i assume chuck's dream is to always be well-fed and cuddled). i was warmly welcomed by these guys from the moment i walked into their apartment. we share a best friend, and, by extension, they instantly made me feel like a friend as well. i was most pleasantly taken aback by their love for one another: they are childhood friends who have lived together for years, yet still make the time to frequently sit down for family dinners and support each other at the drop of a hat. their friendship runs like a well-oiled machine, and it is inspiring. 
these guys renewed my belief that friendships are one of the purest, most noble possessions that we can acquire in our lifetime. people, things, jobs... they come and go. the few humans who remain by our side and support us through the highs and the lows, however, are worth every ounce of our love and loyalty. friendship is a pact, and those who truly commit to it, do not lose it. #thenomadsoasisproject #celinnesoasis

__label__Melbourne,Victoria,Australia you define what is important to you by what you dedicate your time to ✨~ this can be applied to every aspect of our lives from family, friends, work, self- care, personal development, etc... over my journey the last few months, i've been practicing letting go of the energies & things that don't serve me. when i feel "let down" or frustrated when i'm not able to complete my to-do list, when a friendship moves on or reminding my husband to make his health appointments 🙊🤦‍♀️ for example, i'll no longer question if it was me or if my expectations are too high because little by little, i'm truly understanding that everyone's priorities are different. i won't always get it right but i'll keep practicing and i'll practice being present, positive, grateful & mindful for what is in front of me.

__label__ZionNationalPark a few years ago i backpacked the narrows with my mom. and like all adventures i take my mom on, it did not go as smoothly as planned. highlights included forgetting to tell her that the narrows is full of water, hiking through the night with only one working headlamp and one set of trekking polls between the two of us, missing our camp spot, hitch hiking back to our car, and the crazy person screaming in the distance all night long (only my mom heard that part). but practice makes perfect, and this time i was a lot more prepared. although i still had to learn the wet way that the shortest distance between two points is not always the fastest. 😉

__label__Bali,Indonesia new year... old you 🤔? 2019 is here and you may be feeling excited for a fresh start. new goals! lose weight! have more free time! get that promotion!
⠀⠀⠀ ⠀
so you start off strong doing the thing... going to the gym, eating salads, working on your side hustle, being a superstar at work.
⠀⠀⠀ ⠀
but after a few months, you find yourself right back to your normal routine and you’re wondering why you couldn’t achieve your goals the way you envisioned. so you tell yourself that new years resolutions are stupid, that you didn’t care about those goals anyway, or that you set your standards too high.
⠀⠀⠀ ⠀
sorry love but i’m here to tell you these are just excuses.
⠀⠀⠀ ⠀
your new goals aren’t being met because you’re still operating as the old you. are you changing your habits so they’re sustainable long-term? are you doing the inner work to untangle your limiting beliefs? are you seeking the support you need so you’re overcoming obstacles?
⠀⠀⠀ ⠀
in other words... are you working towards the new version of who you want to be?
⠀⠀⠀ ⠀
becoming that person who is fit, healthy, works hard, and gets massively rewarded for your efforts is totally achievable - but first you need to commit to taking the steps to become him/her.
⠀⠀⠀ ⠀
so, how can you begin?
⠀⠀⠀ ⠀
when you set your new year’s goals, make a plan for yourself: for 1 year, then 6 months, 3 months, and the next 30 days. map it out, with milestones and checklists. do the work. check in with yourself. and instead of focusing only on the result (e.g. “i want to lose 10 lbs”), think about the process and the habits you need to develop to get there (e.g. “i am learning to exercise regularly, eat healthier, etc”).
⠀⠀⠀ ⠀
small, actionable, and measurable steps will take you so far, and before you know it, a year will have passed and you’ll have accomplished big things 🤩.
⠀⠀⠀ ⠀
btw, i actually teach you how to take your big dreams and turn them into everyday actionable steps in module 3 of my life design mindset course. when you’re ready to design a lifestyle you love and turn your dreams into a reality, check it out 😀.
⠀⠀⠀ ⠀
what are some big goals you have for 2019?

__label__Colorado “pilates develops the body uniformity, corrects wrong posture, restores physical vitality, and elevates the spirit” - joseph pilates. ————————————————
i remember this beautiful day and mini-hike. i wasn’t feeling that well but it was so beautiful outside i just kept wanting to go to the mountains and be in nature. (swipe left to see beautiful, beauuuutiful colorado scenery) i also remember that before i went on my mini solo adventure, i did pilates. i spend at the very minimum 20 minutes of my day doing my own practice (i know- this sounds like little to some, and often it is far more, but it does every single thing joseph pilates said. i also think it’s important for instructors to do their own practice regularly so we don’t forget what our clients are experiencing and feeling, for the often, the first time.) well, my little session did just that! i was so invigorated, refreshed, and energized that i ended up having this super special day exploring and enjoying nature in peace. 🙏🏼🙏🏼
————————————————
all to say that i encourage everyone to find a little something in their lives that helps press the “reset” button when they need it. passion and movement, even if done or experienced briefly or on a small scale can be so powerful! as can nature 💗💗 if anyone’s been feeling down lately, start with something super simple like a 15 minute walk. just see - even if it’s the last thing you feel like doing. or spend 10 minutes a day learning a new language or skill or some activity you’ve always wanted to try 💗💗 for me, the thing i always come back to is pilates 🙏🏼🙏🏼

__label__Vietnam ⠀
⠀интересные факты❗️
⠀⠀
⠀вьетнам — одна из самых самобытных стран юго-восточной азии. ⠀великолепная нетронутая природа, особый национальный колорит, множество исторических достопримечательностей делают эту страну одним из самых популярных туристических направлений последних лет даже для путешественников с ограниченным бюджетом✅
⠀
⠀представляю топ- 9 неожиданных фактов, которые позволят лучше узнать эту чудесную страну⭐️ ⠀
⠀1. национальный напиток вьетнама – настойки на змеях. их изготавливают из рисового вина или хлебного спирта и употребляют при любом удобном случае 🐍 ⠀
⠀2.  самый популярный вид транспорта в стране – скутер. ежедневно на дороги вьетнама выезжает до 10 млн водителей 🏍 ⠀
⠀3. важной особенностью является размер транспорта. чем больше транспорт, тем больше у него привилегий (ему уступают дорогу, не мешают, не подрезают т.д.) 🚍 ⠀
⠀4. в национальном парке фонгня-кебанг в провинции куангбинь находится самая большая в мире пещера (шондонг) ⛰ ⠀
⠀5.  около 45% граждан вьетнама носят фамилию нгуен (nguyễn). кстати! большинство кафе, парикмахерских, магазинов имеют в своем названии приписку нгуен🙋🏽‍♀️ ⠀⠀
⠀6. вместо привычного для нас звонка во вьетнамских школах используется гонг 🔔 ⠀
⠀7.  на междугородних маршрутах во вьетнаме курсируют спальные автобусы (sleeper bus)😴 ⠀
⠀8. вьетнамская валюта (донги) сделана не из бумаги, а из каучука (полимерные деньги). они кстати гораздо дороже в изготовлении, но зато не намокают и не рвутся💰 ⠀
⠀9. во вьетнамском языке имеется шесть различных тоновых оттенков. использование другого тона в корне меняет смысл слова, так что даже не пытайтесь самостоятельно освоить этот язык🤬 ⠀
⠀10. вьетнамцы довольно радушный и гостеприимный народ, но излишнего проявления чувств они не приемлют. так например, лучше избегать прикосновений к голове и плечам вьетнамцев, по верованиям этого народа подобными действиями вы можете навлечь беду❌
⠀
⠀а вы были во вьетнаме? подметили ещё какие-то интересные особенности этой страны? расскажите нам о них в комментариях!
⠀

абсурдность ситуации сводится к тому, что закон регулирует только вес ручной клади и список предметов разрешенных к провозу сверх этого списка. победа, пользуясь отсутствием точных формулировок устанавливает издевательскую глубину ручной клади в 4 сантиметра. но получается что с собой все еще можно взять рюкзак с габаритами уменьшенными на эти 4 см – 36х30х23см. то есть суммарно основная ручная кладь и дополнительный рюкзак из списка будут занимать объем старого калибратора. но сверху и абсолютно бесплатно можно взять оставшиеся вещи из списка по 1 штуке без ограничения веса и размеров.
⠀
одновременно с этим победа сохранит старые правила: «..мы сохраняем действующей и привычную клиентам редакцию – без ограничений по весу, количеству мест и внешнему виду перевозимых предметов. теперь клиенты могут сами выбрать, какими правилами им удобнее пользоваться: как раньше взять в салон любое количество мест багажа любого типа и веса, но в рамках установленных производителем габаритов 36х30х27см, или руководствоваться новыми правилами, и взять в салон только одно место ручной клади весом до 10 кг и габаритами до 36х30х4см плюс перечень вещей из федеральных авиационных правил, «очевидно относящихся к числу малогабаритных».

__label__Florence,Italy it feels like it was just yesterday. i was a junior in college, boarding a flight all alone to italy, my mom was holding me and bawling (seriously she wouldn’t let me go 😂), and i was a complete mess. i got on the plane and proceeded to cry for a solid 3 hours in to the flight. i voraciously journaled my feelings, ate way too many brownies, and watched “eat, pray, love” in an attempt to get it together.
_
looking back, i was a little overly dramatic and i quote per my italy journal, “i just keep picturing myself crying alone in my room at night hating my decision to come over here.”
_
lol i mean, i was going to italy for crying out loud—- but, it was terrifying at the time. a new place, a new school, i didn’t know anyone, and just being away from home for a whole semester had me all up in my feelings. ahhh my sweet little 21 year old self.
_
it’s honestly funny looking back on it now, knowing that studying abroad was one of the best experiences of my life. it completely took me out of my comfort zone and helped me grow and mature so much as a person and an artist.
_
i love florence so much for that reason alone, and because it really changed everything for me.
_
this summer, i am so ready to head back there again, but this time for a new reason! i get to teach a group of you all in the studio that i learned at, all those years ago!! i’m sure i will have all the same nervous feelings, but i just love the butterflies you get when boarding a flight to go somewhere or do something you’ve never done before.
_
i hope you all will join me on this new adventure!! i have a few spots left and they are open to anyone and everyone who is interested in creating, exploring and meeting other inspiring people!
_
for more information on my florence, italy painting retreat, head to the link in my bio! i’d love to be your personal travel agent and host you all in my favorite place ever! i can already taste the gelato now🍨!! #kaylaweberartgoesabroad

__label__Singapore #ad whether i'm in the mountains, cruising along the coast, or exploring a new city, every experience is so unique and they’ve all contributed to make me who i am today. every place i’ve been has something to offer, but it’s rare to visit a place that has a more perfect mix of rich culture and ultramodern city life than i found in singapore. my trip with @united was an unforgettable experience on board as well as on the ground with so many moments that i’ll cherish for a long time and let’s just say, it's not everyday you get to go for a morning swim in an infinity pool overlooking the entire city. i'll be back soon, singapore! #unitedjourney

__label__Dublin,Ireland just a simple window reflection with the focus point set on the @thetemplebarpub. took a few attempts with this as it was shot handheld at 1/50 shutter speed so i had to be very steady with my hands to eliminate shake. then with the iso pushing 1600 i knew i was risking some noise if i  pushed any further. aperture was f2.8 and focal length 24mm. its certainly not perfect but i am not chasing perfection. we all worry so much when we start sharing photos online and getting feedback on them instantly. we are free to create whatever we want as much or as little as we want. doesn't matter if someone doesn't like it. they don't have to. you do. don't let anything hold you back from your dreams or your content on your page. the only person you are really playing against is yourself. as long as you accept that and understand that you don't need to compare yourself to anyone else you will be ultimately free. get that photo that's sitting on your hard drive for ages that you like, get it edited and post it tonight. don't put it off. don't even wait for the "golden hour" just get it up and share your work. too many of us are holding back thousands of amazing photos, videos and creations because we fear what others think. remember that in decades from now this will all be a memory. go out there today or whenever you are ready and create your history 💪 don't wait too long cause in a flash it will all be over. ❤️

__label__SriLanka .
4 feb 2019.
.
sri lanka achieved independence from the great britain in 4 feb 1948, and today is her 71st independence day.
.
every year during the national day celebration, the president of sri lanka would invite leaders from other countries to come in and join him & his people in the celebration held at galle face. this year, the president of maldives & his wife graced the event as guests of honour, while last year it was prince edward of england. elaborate army parade, cultural performances and festivities were organised nationwide to mark the occasion.
.
we didn’t go out to town until after the main parade was done at around noon. so no photos of the main event taking place today.
.
happy 71st independence day, sri lanka.
.

__label__Denver,Colorado wanderlust: kids fly free on select frontier flights! recently, frontier airlines released that they will allow kids under the age of 15 to fly free if an accompanying adult is a member of the discount den travel club. most airlines start charging kids at age 3, so this new promotion could definitely help make travel fit into your family’s budget. to be noted: the discount den membership costs $59.99 per year, but you have access to lower priced flights and you may use the discounted rate for up to six people on the same itinerary. those savings can definitely add up! ✈️ the kids fly free program is limited to specific dates with limited available quantity per date🧒 but, if you travel often and frontier is a regular option, i highly recommend joining their membership program. plus, create a reward id for free to start accumulating miles to work toward earning a free flight! ps i just earned a “free” one way flight with frontier from past travel! i’m super excited to redeem it and only pay the taxes and fees! 👨‍👩‍👧‍👦 so checkout frontier’s availability in your city and explore their serviced cities. this may turn out to be a huge savings tool to help you travel more often 🗺 📸 from frontier airlines and condé nast traveler

__label__Iceland wanted to thank everyone for all the support you’ve given me in my photography career and all the kind comments you leave on pics/videos. i’ve been thinking a lot lately about this wild path instagram has taken me down and what the future will look like. i’m very early into my photography career and lately been finding my interests drifting towards tech, startups, and projects in those industries. that’s one of the reasons getting involved with @explorest has been such a fun venture for me. one of the reasons i left electrical engineering was i felt the experiences i was having traveling, meeting incredible people, and seeing places i had only dreamed of visiting, outweighed the benefits of my position at the time. the road has been wild and one of the better decisions i’ve made. the thing i tell people i miss most about my old job is the intellectual stimulation, feeling of building something on a team, and working towards a common goal. traveling and sharing the world through my eyes will do for now but i got my eyes fixed on the horizon for the next big thing. sorry this turned into a diary entry/resume but hope me sharing my thoughts from time to time helps provide a little bit more insight into the person behind the pictures. would love to hear more about what you guys do and your backgrounds!

.

__label__Queenstown,NewZealand so, as i mentioned last month when i went scuba diving, i'm kind of scared of water. can't you tell? 😂
.
despite the sheer look of terror on my face (which i had to share, because it's hilarious), river-boarding in queenstown was actually riveting. the experience reminded me of a lesson i've learned repeatedly during my travels: we cannot let our fears dictate how we live our lives.
.
was i nervous about river-boarding? yes. did that stop me from doing it? no. one of my favorite moments was when i was spinning around in a whirlpool, starting to freak out, and the instructor said: "just let it spin you and you'll come right out. don't fight it."
.
ain't that right. sometimes life will spin you around relentlessly, and you have a choice: fear and fight the process, or stay calm and have faith that you'll get out of it eventually. either way, you're there... so it's up to you to enjoy the ride.
.
huge thanks to the amazing crew at serious fun riverboarding for making me feel safe and taken care of (and for the hysterical photos)!
.

__label__Vancouver,BritishColumbia vancouver harbour is absolutely beautiful albeit absolutely freezing cold! after a nice breakfast i decided to venture to the waters edge and take in the stunning scenery. the seaplanes take off and land from here incase you feel like getting an aerial view of the city, and there are some gorgeous cafes and restaurants along the edge of the city. 🗻⚓️🗻⚓️🗻⚓️🗻⚓️
one thing i did notice whilst walking around is that underneath almost every row of trees that line the streets downtown, there are tiny leaf shapes imprinted into the concrete; and yes this may sound like something irrelevant and pointless, but anything that can put a smile on my face just by walking down the street looking at the floor is worthy of a mention in my eyes! has anyone else ever noticed these leaves?
🍁🍃🍂🍁🍃🍂🍁
simple, yet brilliantly effective, i wouldn’t expect anything less from the clever canadian people!

__label__India “i had been waiting for a while to get my hands on this book. i initially thought of reading it in one go but it is very emotional and would have served injustice to the journey. it's very emotional and for a moment made me nostalgic on certain parts. i have finished only till chapter 4 and i am looking to read it as slowly and as deeply as possible...”
~ review for the shooting star on @amazondotin
.
.
i’m absolutely overwhelmed by all your love for my book so far. thanks for sharing your excitement of receiving the book on your instagram stories, for your messages about how you’ve personally connected with parts of the book, for your tweets and dms, and most of all, for your heartfelt reviews on amazon. i’m grateful to have the best readers in the world 🙏
.
.
many of you have asked: what is my dream for this book? it is that every person who reads it is inspired to see the world differently, to ask questions about things that are expected of us (especially in india), to challenge conventions we’ve grown up with. maybe after you’re done reading, you can give the book to someone struggling with these conventions. maybe when you see your friends next, you can plant the seed of challenging conventions in your conversations. the book is just an idea of a different life, an idea that i dream will travel far...
.
.
have you received your copy of the shooting star yet?
.
.
ps: the kindle version of the book is also available on amazon now!
.
.

__label__Ubud this is grandpa (real name is made marka, but he goes by grandpa), one of my hosts in ubud, bali. grandpa also happens to be a balinese priest and a spiritual healer (for those of you who watched/read "eat, pray, love," he was in the same class/trained by the same high priest as ketut and knew him well).
.
i was invited to come stay in a house in the middle of a village about 2km from central ubud. smack dab in the middle of the famous rice fields, my accommodation was very simple: we're talking squatty toilet with a manual flush, bucket showers, cows, pigs, and roosters who woke me up at 4:30 am with their crows. despite the lack of luxuries, i didn't want to leave that place - my time there, soaking up the calm and peace of that environment, renewed me to my core. .
.
grandpa didn't speak a word of english, yet we somehow managed to have some deep conversations. with the help of my other hosts, who translated, i was taught about the balinese philosophy of leading with your heart versus your mind (post on that coming up). i learned that each of us is born with a brother and a sister, spiritual entities who know what you need even when you're not aware and don't want to admit it. these "siblings" - represented by the placenta - use their energy to help you meet the people who can help you throughout your life.
.
the sheer power of grandpa's presence healed me. i understood so much about myself, much of which i'm till processing and will share this week. my time in that house was yet another reminder that understanding someone goes far, far beyond the spoken word. we are all connected, and once we tap into the energy of that network... that's when we begin to understand that god is but one force, split amongst 7+ billion.
.

__label__Mumbai,Maharashtra as a common sandpiper amused me and my camera while strolling in the jogger's park around the vashi holding pond, a jogger saw me taking photographs of the bird and asked me:

jogger: hi, do you want to take photographs of a snake?
nitsbee: yes, of course! why not?
jogger(smiling and pointing to the shrubs a little ahead from where we were standing): there it is among the bushes. it has come out now. you can find it there.
nitsbee: ohh cool! thanks.

i still couldn't see the snake and walked a little ahead towards the shrubs to where the jogger pointed out. i stood steady and glanced everywhere on the grounds to find the snake. suddenly saw some dried foliage moving on the ground just 5 meters from where i was standing and saw the snake slithering past me. "click click click went my camera". other joggers saw me and were curious as to why i was pointing my camera towards the ground and they realised it was a snake. soon, other joggers gathered around to see the snake. the snake slithered away soon into the dense foliage and disappeared. plenty of shots that i took. i realised it was the first time that i've ever photographed a snake. wasn't even on my bucket list. couldn't identify the snake but my best guess is that it is rat snake. let me know the correct species if i'm wrong. .
.
.
.
1/1600s : f/6.5 : iso 800
.
.

__label__CentralPark now that i’m home and know i’ll be in new york city for most of the month, i cannot. wait. for. the. leaves. to. turn. 🍁🍂 so the whole city is colorful and crisp. i love autumn. i think it’s my favorite season in the city. my only complaint is that no one has a food truck selling cider and apple orchard donuts. (business opportunity alert‼️) because i crave them both at this time of year after growing up with them and it’s not that easy to just pop upstate to a cider mill when you don’t own a car. which is funny, in that when i first moved to this city, i had grand plans of road trips every weekend and lots of sightseeing along the eastern seaboard as well as new england. i dreamed of always being back up in vermont, my home state, at this time of year. but those schemes and dreams died a quick death when i realized it’s actually easier and cheaper to just fly to paris if you can’t own a car. i remember one summer when @dante.vincent and i rented a car with some friends to go on a weekend adventure and even splitting it four ways still ended up being more expensive than a plane ticket..... well that was a tangent but if there’s a lesson to be learned i think it’s that life doesn’t always go the way you think it will; what’s important is to love the life you do have! 💛 #newyorkcity #autumninnewyork #centralparknyc #newyorkornowhere #autumncolors #latergramsfordays #iloveny

__label__Asia/Singapore //boudoir//
6. mini sunflowers [repost]
@sabrinagahni_ was so different 4 years ago too. there was one time last year where i had a panic attack and the first person i called was her. after one missed call she called me back within seconds asking if i was okay and calmed me down over the phone. 
sabrina is a person that surprises, because a long time ago i never thought i’d make that call to her and after a conversation, i realised she never thought that she would have gone through what she did in 4 years to answer that call and calmed me down the way she did.
i always told myself that 16 year old me would be devastated at the person i’ve become. but perhaps while i expected to be a sunflower, i became a yellow daisy instead. i joked with sabrina how it’s “second-rate” to not quite hit the mark, but looking at this photo perhaps that all i’ve expected myself to be needed a tweak in perspective. a bunch of yellow daisies are just as beautiful. #boudoirphotography

__label__Kyoto,Japan after the initial high of getting lucky enough to see the sakura in bloom in japan, i felt pretty overwhelmed. by their extravagant beauty, by the crowds everywhere i tried to go, by the pressure to photograph them like everyone else and in knowing that this beauty is just fleeting... .
.
after running around for a day in kyoto, trying to glimpse the sakura in places everyone said i couldn’t miss and failing to get a quiet moment with these beauties, i stopped. this isn’t how i like to travel, i remembered. .
.
so the next morning, i ditched the bus pass, borrowed a bicycle from my japanese host and just wandered around the streets with no particular place in mind. in a neighbourhood park, where locals were jogging and walking their dogs, i finally found the connection i was looking for. the inspiration to sit under a cherry tree, gaze at the fleeting beauty and pen fleeting thoughts in my notebook. .
.
i think the key to really savouring your travels (and life) is being you. chasing your bliss and not someone else’s 🐾
.
.
#theshootingstar #sakurajapan #kyoto #shotoniphone #writersofig

__label__Helsinki i’ve just finished answering everyone who commented on my last post (i asked how you really feel & what’s on your mind right now) and holy shit, there is a big elephant in the room you guys...
⠀⠀⠀ ⠀
we don’t talk about how we feel. does this sound familiar:
⠀⠀⠀ ⠀
person: “hey, how are you?”
you: “yeah i’m great, and yourself?”
person: “great thanks!”
*end of interaction*
⠀⠀⠀ ⠀
at any given moment, one of us is hurting. we have so much turbulence in our minds... stress, anxiety, worries, etc. why aren’t we sharing how we really feel with one another?
⠀⠀⠀ ⠀
i don’t know about you, but i want to be able to talk about my weaknesses, to feel safe expressing myself, to not be embarrassed about admitting, “hey, actually i’m not doing so well, i’d love to chat about it.” no one is going to give you permission to do this... only you can.
⠀⠀⠀ ⠀
respect your pain. you don’t have to hide how you really feel and by airing it out, you give yourself room to heal. the cool part is, you help those around you feel more comfortable with doing it, too.
⠀⠀⠀ ⠀
it’s ultimately up to us to 1. share ourselves fully and 2. hold the space for others to do it, too. don’t hold back, my friends.
⠀⠀⠀ ⠀
here’s a challenge for you: can you make space for somebody today? one meaningful conversation? report back in the comments below and i’ll respond!
⠀⠀⠀ ⠀

__label__Dubrovnik,Croatia my first day in #dubrovnik, i decided to take the cable car up the mountain to see the sunset and city from above. little did i know it would turn into a spectacular memory. in addition to the sunset being stunning (expected), there were so many wild horses! i spotted one in the distance and decided to follow it, and eventually it led me to the others. en route i made a buddy, who was also photographing the horses. together we trekked through the landscape - it began getting dark quite quickly as the sky prepared for a massive thunderstorm. it was like something out of a movie: exploring on top of dubrovnik, overlooking the poetic #oldcity, watching wild horses roam as lighting and thunder struck in the background. it was quite idyllic prior to me running back to the cable car and getting soaked, of course.
but so worth it.
moments like these remind me why a life of travel is the way 🤗

__label__ZionNationalPark the infamous subway hike in zion...one of my favorite hikes we've done this year. technically called the left fork of north creek canyon, it is much better known for its resemblance to an underground subway. we did what is called the bottom-up route, which is basically hiking through the river to get to the subway (rather than the top-down approach, which involves rappelling down into the canyon). whichever way you go, the end goal is this beautiful scene right here. this long cylindrical tunnel of sandstone has to be one of zion's more interesting geological features. it is a lot of fun to photograph as well. if you are thinking of doing the subway hike or rappel, make sure you get a permit at the nps wilderness office

__label__Zanzibar,Tanzania ignorance begets "confidence" than does knowledge. it can be scary to open up self to others and new experiences (cultures, food, language etc) and with that we bottle ourselves in our cocoons of false confidence.
best to spend our time in joy of opening up to learning and discovering with love and humility, than creating barriers with fear and division.
inshallah, one day we shall be one people, and till then it is us who have to create the possibility of that future. 📸 we had been invited as special guests to a mosque opening by the community whom we are embedded with. such a lovely day it was.

__label__Amsterdam,Netherlands sharing some big news today...after two years of calling amsterdam home, we’ve decided to pack up our bags and travel full time. 
we’ve spent the last couple of weeks packing boxes, moving things into storage, and getting ready for this adventure. this is totally new to us- when we moved abroad, we left l.a. on a road trip through europe and had a set plan. now we’ll be traveling indefinitely, with our backpacks (ok, and suitcases 😂). we have loads of exciting things in the works these next few months that we can’t wait to start sharing 🙌🏼
i’m working on a blog post on what living abroad and travel blogging has really been like & what brought us here. until then, here are some of our favorite moments from our lives in amsterdam these past couple years - swipe for more photos! the first one is from our last night in our apartment ✨✨

__label__Thailand [i can't make this up] what inspires me to write is just memories from the past. everything comes from things i’ve been through. sometimes it can be just me seeing things other people have been through that i could relate to. it’s not always just about my memory. so i create an image in my head. someone recently said to me “you smile so often in your snaps, are there ever any bad days?” like you and everyone else who’s reading, i’m human. my bad days, however, are really bad. i experience a lot of frustration. sometimes when i’m writing these journals i don’t want to remember my past.. the streets, the rejection, the shame. then i don’t want to be selfish and not tap into the realness of my life. to ease my way out of frustration is by writing it out and creating art. it’s really hard to describe how i feel when i take a photo or when i’m out on the road. it’s just a temporary get away from the problems, and you know.. that’s good enough for me. and then when i really think about it i guess i’m doing ok for someone that was labeled “special ed” and below reading level? although my writing isn’t perfect, i can admit now that it’s gradually gotten better. kinda. for those of you guys who spend the time to read these long captions that i write it truly does mean a lot. i’ve always had the problem of over thinking and putting myself out there to the world. but i had to really look at myself in the mirror and remind myself that i don’t ever want to be scared to tell my story. so i hope that by reading this that you feel comfortable enough to even share yours. either with me in the comments below or even in a dm. i’ll be your pen pal, your homie from the cyberwebz. since you made it this far if you're feeling this let me know by commenting #fammmm.
___________

__label__RiodeJaneiro,RiodeJaneiro aquí tenemos una foto del "real gabinete portugues da leitura" en río de janeiro, brasil. esta biblioteca tiene mas libros escrito en portugues, afuera de portugal, que todas las bibliotecas en el mundo. construido en el estilo gótico-renacentista (llamada estilo manueline en portugues, del rey manuel), es considerada una de las bibliotecas mas bella del mundo. la biblioteca fue establecida en el año 1837, durante el imperio de brasil. la construccíon comenzó con el emperador pedro ii y terminó con su hija, isabel, la princesa imperial de brasil. que piensan de esta biblioteca? les gusta?

__label__Edinburgh,UnitedKingdom somebody asked me just now  why i was so excited about all the likes for my posts.
⠀⠀
when i write my posts that is the way i am talking to all of you, those 4500 people.
yea, i am not some kind of big blogger, but this number is huge! imagine 4500 people in your house! and my page is my house!
⠀⠀
every single one of you of that number is a person. with heart, with soul, with worries, with smile.
⠀⠀
when you press that like button, that is the way you communicate with me. 
when i check if you guys press that heart button for my post it shows that you understand my message, what i want to say, so i don’t feel like talking to myself or send message into space for aliens! 😅
⠀⠀
if you feel like pressing that like-button press then, if you don’t then don’t, i don’t do my posts for statistics, but if you like to read it, or it helps, or you can relate, it is always good to know that...
⠀⠀
so let me know. in comment, in like, in direct message.
⠀⠀
instagram is social network. 
social means interaction, communication.
⠀⠀
and i would like to communicate with all of  you, to get to know each and one of you better. what’s your opinions, what’s your thoughts, goals, achievements, worries and doubts.
⠀⠀
don’t be shy! 
i can listen. that’s my job at the end of the day.
.
.

__label__OahuLife this is what i imagine living within your truth looks like. simple. clear. not necessarily a direction but a state of being. i’ve been feeling cluttered lately, murky in my own skin. sad about so many tragedies. it’s why i’ve been quiet on here, sort of feeling the weight of both inner and outer worlds. 
so hi, this is me. i’m mostly happy, sometimes sad both in the same moment. i’m trying to balance being real with showing the world my best self, while a voice says maybe those are the same selves. i believe that truths can contradict yet coexist. that what’s important sometimes feels impossible...but only at the beginning. and that finding clarity in this world means diving in. being patient when the wind and salt scrub against the messiness of your mind. #notestoselfseries
-
pc @jdbaluch

__label__Tokyo,Japan i’m not even sure how i first hear of this warehouse in tokyo. i wasn’t sure what to expect either, but from the very first moment i entered this place i felt like i stepped into a cyberpunk dystopian city straight out of blade runner but weirder. from hallways to the bathrooms, everything is covered in fake filth to make it look like the hong kong’s kowloon walled city. but hey, it’s actually a modern day arcade with so many claw machines - you can even fish out some ice cream. 
i think it was one of the coolest off the path experiences i had in japan.

__label__NewZealand my whole life i’ve always been told that my face reads like an open book. unable to hide my feelings and emotions, what you see is what you get. can you tell what i’m thinking here? if you’re first guess was “fuck mornings, give me coffee” then yes, you are correct. but it’s also much more than this. as i look at my face in this picture, it really sums up the past few months for me. i’m chronically exhausted, stressed to the max and beyond tired, and yet trying to find a little glimmer of something to make me smile, which is harder every day. burnt out doesn’t begin to cover it. with my insomnia back in full swing, my anxiety keeping me company every waking hour, and a punishing travel schedule that i just couldn’t say no to, i only blame myself for getting to this point.  living in a competitive world if you’re not “busy” or “great” than you’re lazy and unsuccessful, and the pressure of this path i’ve been on is often suffocating, and it often feels like my creativity has gone forever. without realizing it, i’ve slipped into the habit of only showing the glamor of travel, of my world. normally i would have posted a different version of this shot, where my tired face is hidden or later on when i’ve had 3 coffees and put on makeup, perhaps with an inspirational caption about following your dreams. but part of me has always been an honest cynic, and i’m tired. i’m tired of everything. here is a moment of reality. i look and feel like shit, but i’m trying to do my best and do my job. i love it but it’s hard. we are all imperfect humans full of complex emotions, me included. you are not alone. now where is the coffee? #inspirationalandallthatshit #lookwhatthecatdraggedin

__label__Tokyo,Japan in the early days of building @beautifuldestinations we did a trip to japan that will stick with me for life. i loved the people, the culture, the food and the feeling of being in a completely different environment where the only way to communicate (as i don’t speak japanese) is with a smile and a positive outlook 😎 that mindset has served me well in every country i’ve been to and with the rugby world cup next year and the olympics the year after i cannot wait for millions more people to experience such a special country 🇯🇵

__label__Kyoto,Japan there’s no city i’ve been to (yet) that compares to the beauty of kyoto. every street i walked, every cafe, shop, hostel, hotel is consistently clean and beautiful. even the locals walk around with smiles on their faces. something you don’t see often in london! 🎌 ⠀
⠀

__label__Shanghai,China happy chinese new year! 新年快樂 🇨🇳🎉 this year is the year of the pig. fun fact: i am born in the year of the pig 🐷

fun fact 2: while i’m born and raised in australia (and i always get mistaken for korean) my fam is from shanghai and i can speak shanghainese!

fun fact 3: business hub cities like shanghai is quite empty around the new year cause those who came here for work would go back to their hometown. so when i went back, i couldn’t get some of my favourite food cause almost all street food and small businesses were closed 😅

fun fact 4: chinese new year is usually the only of time of the year people would go on holiday. it lasts 2 weeks during which you gather and feast with your extended fam starting from the cny eve to the third day after cny (at least in my fam), and then travel for the remaining.

fun fact 5: number 4 is an unlucky number in china hence for fun fact 5 😂 during cny, if you’re unmarried in your fam, you’ll receive red pockets (hong bao 红包) filled with cash from relatives and family friends 🧧

__label__Bali today, in the little village of gobleg in the hills of munduk, i met a traditional balinese healer (locally called a balian). he is a farmer, but several years ago, people realized that his massages were healing. when someone in the village has muscle aches or broken bones, they don't go to the hospital; they go to him first.
.
.
when i asked him how long since the realization, he laughed and said he doesn't even know how old he is! there were no records back in the day, and many balinese elders don't know when their birthday is. i'd peg him at 80-90 years, but he's still very fit and has happy lines on his face 👀
.
.
he gave me a healing massage, and at first, i was quite tensed about how it would turn out. then he massaged the tension points in my head and i felt light as a feather and tuned in to his constant chatting (in balinese though). he said something about india, something about yoga, something about the stresses i'm carrying around. meeting him was inexplicably rejuvenating 😇
.
.
also gobleg, such a pretty little village with rice paddies, marigold fields and wild flowers 💙
.
.
#theshootingstar #bali #indtravel

__label__Dubrovnik,Croatia even though i write a lot about adventurous activities or bucket list experiences, one of my favorite things to do when i travel is actually pretty simple. there is nothing better than sitting outside at a cafe anywhere in europe when it's warm and sunny outside; glass of wine and snacks included of course. i don't know why, but being a part of this communal activity is so relaxing and so therapeutic for me that i relish any opportunity to enjoy it. now that summer is in full swing, i'm excited for my next trip starting this weekend as i board a flight for germany, but that's not what i want to share today, instead it's this image from the always amazing dubrovnik, croatia. 
the old town in dubrovnik can definitely get busy, but as late afternoon dissolves into early evening the streets clear out and you're left with this glittering city all to yourself. there's a reason why "game of thrones" uses it to film their king's landing shots, it feels like the city jumped out of a fantasy novel. 
walking down along the limestone-paved stradun - the main thoroughfare in town - i turned right and found this cafe near the rector's palace. in one scene, i had found everything i love about europe. it was a beautiful day, not too hot during the day or too chilly at night, and everyone was out and about enjoying the perfect weather while it lasted. this cafe in central dubrovnik was popular and with good reason. sitting there chatting with friends, enjoying a glass of crisp croatian white wine and spending hours people watching is the height of travel perfection. while the major attractions are always fun to visit, it's experiencing the laid back vibe of the mediterranean that's even more special; understanding the city by living it instead of just seeing it.

__label__Naples,Italy неаполь: итоги 🇮🇹 странное впечатление на меня произвёл неаполь. с одной стороны, он в чем-то даже красивее рима: в нем есть прекрасная набережная, здания удивляют своими яркими цветами, а каждый переулок открывает сюрпризы в виде зелёных садов на крыше (их выложу позже) или входов в старейшие соборы италии. с другой же, несмотря на это и потрясающую кухню, тут творится мусорный ад, раздолье преступности и непредсказуемое поведение случайных прохожих, часть которых, определенно, готова сравнять иностранца с землёй. пусть он такой, для меня все-таки главное — что это европа, хоть и не та, о которой все мечтают. она запущенная, но прекрасная исторически, грязная, но чистая архитектурно и атмосферно. для меня вообще европа является лучшим, что создавало человечество, и я, как сейчас понимаю, могу принять ее даже такой юродивой //
.
.

__label__Brussels,Belgium happy world nutella day to every chocolate-lovin, calorie-cravin, nutella consumer on this planet.

if there's one detail that's common knowledge to anyone who follows my blog, it's my borderline [understatement] obsession with this sinfully delicious goodness called nutella.

i couldn't let this day go by without paying homage to the hazelnut glory that jesus died for our sins to try and save us from.

my best nutella splurges came in belgium with my good friend @nicolasparise, on belgian waffles smothered with that royal cream for $1 and in romania, on cake bread (for 25 cents). 😁

however you're choosing to celebrate this sacred day, i just ask that you keep me in mind when baking your nutella recipes tonight 😂

while @nutella and i are still working through a partnership, i ask that you all make sure to double your usual consumption today.

thank you, nutella, for feeding me, comforting me, and helping me push my limits in life (mainly on the scale, but izall good). marry me, nutella, and let's just give the world the chocolate babies they deserve.

__label__Cusco,Peru for those of you who have been following me and @rickroma’s lost camera/hat saga (we left them in a taxi and the driver never returned them), i am pleased to announce that we are finally reunited with our belongings!
⠀⠀⠀ ⠀
we seriously deserve a detective badge for our persistence in the past 3 days: we traveled back to sacred valley, scoured over video surveillance to identify the car, and worked with police to track down the driver. almost two whole days gone in this hunt, but we found him despite the slim odds!
⠀⠀⠀ ⠀
one of the policemen made an offhand comment that we “must have such a bad impression of peruvians now.”
⠀⠀⠀ ⠀
but the reality is quite the opposite. we may have encountered one naughty peruvian, but we befriended so many good ones because of it. during our fiasco, everyone - strangers on the street, hotel owners, policemen - went above and beyond to help us.
⠀⠀⠀ ⠀
i strongly believe that on the whole, people are good, and i was touched by the peruvians’ kindness. yes, i have my critiques about these countries - aka it’s true that a lot of locals try to rip people off because they are tourists - but in the end, i found myself surrounded by infinitely more good than bad.
⠀⠀⠀ ⠀
peru has for sure earned a special place in my heart!
⠀⠀⠀ ⠀
📷: @rickroma

__label__Delhi,India mornings are starting to become my favorite time of the day, and though 95% of the time i don't wake up to an alarm clock, i'm still an early riser because of the lifestyle i get to live.

i read a quote almost a decade ago, and it completely changed my perspective. "mondays don't suck; it's your life that does." whew, that stung. but oftentimes we're so busy getting offended that we don't let the conviction seep through and do its job.

so i started treasuring my mondays as much as my fridays, and my mornings as much as my evenings.

there's purpose and value in both. but i needed that quote to remind me of that.

what aspect of life are you taking for granted that you're working on changing? let's discuss!

__label__Petra,Ma`An,Jordan i was very honored to spend last week with @contiki x @treadright and activist @celinescousteau learning more about their mission to #maketravelmatter. each day we spent a portion seeing some of jordan’s incredible historic sites (like this here in the ancient city of petra) while also visiting with some amazing women-owned cooperatives like iraq al amir.
.
i love travel. i think it’s been one of the most important factors of growth in my life. but as more of us travel (and especially as i feel i often encourage travel), i often think about practical ways to make our collective impact a positive one. there is no one right approach, but i loved this trip so much because i got to see one possibility of what that might look like.
.
although treadright is a nonprofit, rather than focus on charity, it empowers its local partners with the tools to create viable tourism-based businesses and connects them to a larger network of tour operators (like @contiki). we got to do everything from cooking classes to ceramics, hiking, hand picking figs, and buying unique locally-sourced products. meeting the women of @iraqalamircoop and seeing their sense of pride and ownership over their many projects (among them: running a guest house for hikers on the jordan trail and hosting paper making classes) was equally as interesting and inspiring to me as seeing the windswept canyons of wadi rum.
.
pretty sure no one reads thoughts this long😂 but yea the intersection of all these things just makes me really excited!!☺️
.
ps: i lost all my photos when my phone broke, but for now if you’d like to see more of what we experienced please stop by my storyhighlight or the others on the trip for some really well written thoughts @treadright, @soultravelblog, @alisonsadventures and @celinescousteau. thank you all for an unforgettable trip. blog coming next week x
-

i was riding my motorcycle along a desert road in rajasthan when i observed a lady in a green sari picking olives from a tree. i stopped my motorcycle by the side of the road to ask if i could take her picture. when she saw me approaching she began to run away shouting. i tried calling her to let her know i meant no harm but she couldn’t understand me anyway. a group of men traveling in a tuc tuc saw what was happening and quickly came to her aid. thankfully i managed to explain things to them before matters got out of hand. they then explained things to the lady who agreed to continue picking olives so i could take the picture.
.

__label__Venice,Italy 𝙿𝚛𝚊𝚌𝚝𝚒𝚌𝚎 𝚢𝚘𝚞𝚛 [𝙴𝚗𝚐•𝚕𝚒𝚜𝚑]
⠀
сколько раз внезапно вам нужно было говорить на иностранном языке в россии?
⠀
вчера посчастливилось вести диалог с итальянцем -- у него возникли проблемы при покупке проездного в москве. любопытно, что он знал даже немного русский язык, но его умения разибились о российскую реальность 🤪
⠀
лучшая проверка своих знаний - внезапная практика. это как "готовим двойные листочки" в школе. вот только соображать стоит почти мгновенно и шанса на списывание нет. пускай мы много читаем, смотрим видео на другом языке, это не поможет бегло заговорить. вот так, я забыла слово "сотня». это мне напомнило поездку в америку по work&travel, когда слова из повседневного обихода были полностью забыты, зато навыки делового английского были на высоте. вот только объяснять графики, статьи так и не довелось 🤭
⠀
были времена, когда я учила китайский, потом итальянский - но без практики это знания сейчас практически исчезли.
⠀
сколько языков вы знаете помимо родного: один, два или ни один? и вообще считаете нужным знать иной?

__label__Denver,Colorado exercise is a debt i owe loki and payments are due every day.
_
it could just be luck, but loki is the second northern breed i’ve had that is surprisingly “chill” and relatively well behaved.
and just by coincidence, i exercised the heck out of both of them.
when we’re not on the road or backcountry skiing, loki gets his exercise in the suburbs by running next to a bike.
_
is it dangerous? yeah, a little. 
is running on pavement the best thing for his joints? maybe not. 
one thing i am certain of is that a lot more dogs die of obesity, anxiously escaping from backyards and getting hit by cars, or being put down due to behavioral problems, than dogs running on too much pavement. 
this is the best option i have for intense exercise living in the city.
_
i really don’t care how you run your dog as long as your smart about it,
but i am here to tell you that you owe it to them.
_
leash by @wolfgangmanandbeast x loki

__label__SanFrancisco,California every time i come back to the u.s. after several months or a couple years away, it’s always a bittersweet feeling.

the immigration officer greeted me with the biggest smile, and then i heard the words i don’t hear too often — “welcome home.” little did he know, this was actually the closest i’d get to returning “home” in over 12 years 😱

i drove down highways that led to the church my dad was a pastor at, the hospitals my mom was a nurse at, and where we'd exit to go to nigerian functions every weekend.

fast-forward to my senior year of college four years ago, and i knew leaving this country would be the best thing for me.

though i acknowledge my privilege of owning a first world passport that allows me to leave, i also recognize that same privilege that also allows me to come back.

it was 4am in argentina last november when i watched the final poll counts verify my worst nightmare.

i never felt more let down, betrayed, and disgusted by so many people.

i was numb and i took out my hatred for he who shall not be named and his supporters out on the entire country.

i dissociated myself with america and started referring to the state i was born rather than the country when foreigners would ask, hoping to deflect any conversation about how the heck we got ourselves in this mess. or as they would kindly ask, “what the hell is wrong with you guys over there?!” 🙃

but being back on u.s. soil now has reminded me of the beautiful, vibrant, and diverse souls that still populate this country.

san francisco is a microcosm of the progressiveness and potential this country is known for.

and all it really took were a couple strolls through target and best buy to forgive all sins if we’re being really honest here. 😭

this country is a work in progress. but what country isn’t? its people are healing, hurting, learning, and growing. i am too.

though our differences make us unique, i hope we can unite in advocating for policy change, inclusion, and the never-ending fight against racism and all other forms of discrimination.

thanks @gopro for bringing me back! my liver hates/thanks you for all the fun.
