__label__HoChiMinhCity,Vietnam the joy you get from visiting a country so foreign yet so familiar is unparalleled.

i navigate the beautifully chaotic roads "xin chào'ing" my way between a million and one motorbikes, locals, and people that fill the streets of the vibrant ho chi minh city.

i lived here for a month in 2015 and i'm remembering why it was so hard to leave.

vietnamese people and their culture are so colorfully intoxicating, and i'm having fun speaking their language with all the varied syllabic intonations.

during our gala dinner at @ite.hcmc, we swooned over the cultural performances that graced the stage with such precision and perfection, you couldn't program a machine to do it any better.

stuffing my face in vietnamese cuisine has also been a long overdue treat, for i came with all the elastic dresses in the world to accommodate my inevitably expanding waistline.

regrets still mia.

tune into my ig stories to follow all the behind the scenes action, and a huge thanks to @themystdongkhoi for hosting us in their dope space and all of our wonderful sponsors for this event!

#itehcmc #vietnamtimelesscharm #travelvietnam #vibranthochiminh #internationaltravelexpo

__label__MoraineLake moraine lake, my happy place.
but, when i visited last week at sunrise there was no fewer than 200 people there. i was frustrated. any other sunrise i'd been before there was no more than 2 or 3. 
i posted my frustration in a youtube video, and kind of got hit with some backlash. i kind of think it was justified. 
with so many incredible places to see and photograph in alberta, there's no excuse for whining about an excess of people in the classic locations. it just means we have to dig deeper, explore farther, and step out of our comfort zones. 
that morning was a message to me as a photographer to stop being lazy, and shooting what's easy. continue to grow and search for your own places, and perspectives. it's a big world. there's lots to see. alberta is an amazing place, and there's so much of it i still need to see, shoot and explore. 
#explorealberta #explorecanada

__label__KualaLumpur,Malaysia the kuala lumpur tower (malay: menara kuala lumpur; chinese: 吉隆坡塔;abbreviated as kl tower) is a communications tower located in kuala lumpur, malaysia. its construction was completed on 1 march 1995. it features an antenna that increases its height to 421 metres (1,381 feet) and is the 7th tallest freestanding tower in the world. the roof of the pod is at 335 metres (1,099 feet). the rest of the tower below has a stairwell and an elevator to reach the upper area, which also contains a revolving restaurant, providing diners with a panoramic view of the city.

__label__Venice,Italy venedik’in 400’ü aşkın köprüsü arasında en eskilerinden biri. bir sürü suluboya resmine konu olmuş... girişinden sanki iki pencere açılıyor gibi kanala. zamanla trabzanları aşındığından, yenilenmiş. venedik’in yer yer yıpranan, yosunlarla kaplanan köprüleri, evleri arasında hala ruhunu koruyan bu kadar güzelliğin olmasının ilginç bir sebebi var. venedik şehri kurulduğu zaman yasalar, şehir sakinlerine sadece şehre dair yatırımlar yapmalarına izin veriyormuş. kendilerine harcama yapamayan zengin aileler de, bu şehri daha da zenginleştirip, güzelliğine güzellik katmışlar.✨
🔹🔸🔹
one of those bridges over 400, with renewed handrails between the two old buildings. obviously, venice gets older year after year. but, it’s still captivating despite the enormous rate of tourism or changing environment issues. one the reasons why venice saves the soul is the law bringing into force back in the day, which tried to keep richness of the city by allowing the residents to invest only in the city instead of themselves.💶
.
.

__label__Warsaw,Poland берлін
хоч це місто не топчік серед найпопулярніших #mustsee туристами, проте щось в ньму є😋 🇩🇪топ 10 місць у берліні🇩🇪
10.музейний острів
9.потсдамерплатц - сучасний берлін, будівлі ніби знаходишся у якомусь сінгапурі, такі не типові для більшої частини міста. 🏭 варто подивитися.
8.площа жандермаркт - площа в центрі міста, одна з найкращих в німеччині 
7.берлінський собор - неймовірно красивий.
це найбільша протистанська церква в країні
6.телевежа - свого роду, візитка міста, що знаходиться на александерплатц, де часто проходять різні ярмарки і є купа магазинів із сувенірами.
її видно майже з усіх куточків берліну, тож чому б не роздивитися вежу з близька😏
5.кпп чекпоінт чарлі -  пункт перетину кордону між східним і західним берліном, який існує і до сьогодні, та несе лише символічний характер.  коли там знаходишсь, відчуття ніби потрапив в минуле, або перебуваєш на зйомках історичного фільму про місто до падіння стіни.
4.берлінське метро -одне з найстаріших і найбільших в європі, майже ніколи не переповнене пасажирами. будучи в берліні, покататися на метро - просто необхідність🚈
3.бранденбурзкі ворота - можна сказати, візитна картка берліну.
символ об'єднання міста після падіння берлінської стіну.
2.рейхстаг. екскурсії, до речі, безкоштовні, але потрібно заздалегідь зареєструватися. в екскурсію входить піднятися на купол рейхстагу, послухати аудіогіда російською мовою. триває десь 30 хв.
особисто коли я там була, мене найбільше вразив трансвестит, який там працював, що тут скажеш європа😆 берлін, місто, що дивує😉
1. берлінська стіна, яку я, до речі, знайшла коли приїхала вдруге. адже, якщо у німців запитати де знаходиться берлінська стіна (berlin wall)ми так запитували, то у відповідь чули сміх, або подив, бо за їхніми словами ніякої стіни у них давно немає😁
ми трохи погуглилли і знайшли, що потрібно було запитувати #eastsidegalery, так називається місце, де під відкритим небом знаходяться рештки стіни.
звісно, це просто стіна в графіті, ну але як не зробити фото біля славнозвісного поцілунку. і як не пройти повз частину такої складної історії берліну.

__label__Melbourne,Victoria,Australia a little snippet from my upcoming upper body workout video! 
① australian pull-ups - 4 sets of as many as you can do. this is an easier version to pull-ups. a lot of you guys asked me how i trained for pull ups. i did loads of these and also assisted pull-ups before i could do one pull-up! def try this one!
② inclined push up - 3 sets of as many as you can do. similar as before, if you can’t do a push up, then try this one first. the higher your hands the easier it is because gravity ya know. 
③ tricep kickback - work that arms with this move. keep your upper arm stationary and use your triceps to move the weights and give it a squeeze at the top.

⠀
“ashtanga” do sânscrito “ashta” – oito e “anga” – passos, é citado nos yoga sutras de patanjali, que constitui as fundações completas do ashtanga yoga, também chamada de raja yoga.⠀

__label__NewYork,NewYork [announcement] i grew up in oakland, ca where i thought there wasn’t a life outside of the violent bubble i was living in. with all of the adversity such as both of my parents leaving me at the age of six to my grandfather passing away in middle school i didn’t even think i’d get through high school. with positive influences and a life changing moment with the police i managed to barely be admitted into college where i started my first company and began to travel. then well.. everything that’s happened since has changed my life in such a positive way. i’m excited to announce to you guys that i’ve landed a job in new york and i’ll be leaving with @jlinhh in the beginning of march. i can’t release the details on who i’m working with just yet but know that i’ll be a full time creator! who would’ve known a small town cat like myself would be venturing off to the big city. thank you to everyone who’s been following my journey. i can’t wait to share a new chapter of my life with you all! ➖➖➖➖➖➖➖➖➖➖➖➖➖➖
i’m going to be hosting a garage sale throughout the week to sell of clothes/gear/misc so if you’re in the bay and want to drop by and say hi let me know in the comments below! #andytonewyork

__label__Maldives the storm hit so hard and so quickly we didn’t have time to register that our boat had gone and the only company we had in the middle of the indian ocean was the thirty sharks circling beneath us..... 🦈🦈🦈 but these little guys were so friendly and so curious, they let me dive with them over and over, allowed me to follow them as they explored the depths and even swam right up to me and rubbed their noses on my leg when they got more comfortable :) this is the last shark video i have from the maldives and reminds me that nature has the most amazing way of working in harmony with humans, we just have to make sure we give the same love back and take care of all the animals and environments that exist on our planet 😊🌎 (🎵: “needing you” david morales)

__label__HongKong new blog post: my thoughts on the lack of color in the travel industry #linkinbio

it's a discussion that i get tagged in almost daily in facebook travel groups, so it was long overdue that i put all my thoughts in one place.

blogging is no longer monolithic, and poc influencers exist on every scale of the spectrum.

in a world that tries to paint everything as black and white, there is so much going on in the gray.

the gray of this situation is that i’m doing my best to hustle and grind and make my brand known in a very whitewashed travel industry, regardless of my inherent disadvantage.

but the working twice as hard to get half the recognition gets old quick.

brands, marketers, pr reps, and beyond — if you’re continually contracting the same race, religion, gender, and lifestyle brand of bloggers, you’re doing such a disservice to the public.

exercising diversity isn’t something that should be seen as a chore. you should be excited to amplify the voices of minorities, because it will add a different tone, pun intended, [and market, hello $$$] to the mix.

i also tackle the pervasive "put me on" culture, shout out some of the strongest names in the poc blogging space, and give some insight into how we can solve this issue on a larger scale. *5-minute read

anxious to hear your thoughts ❤ bit.ly/lackofcolor #linkinbio

__label__Jaipur,Rajasthan jaipur, famously renowned as the pink city is the royal capital of india's largest state, rajasthan. jaipur breathes royalty and wealth. with its gigantic forts, alluring palaces and enormous lifestyle, this city well reminds us of the royal era. if these poised attractions do not tend to mesmerize you, then you could always experience the grandness of it by taking an elephant ride in jaipur. it would definitely be a great experience for you to recall for years. every year hundreds of tourists flock towards the amber fort just for this majestic ride. the beauty of these animals decorated in royal colors would definitely ensorcelled you. these enthralling animals also showcase a great amalgam of painted colours which reflect beautifully. this joy ride takes you to the entrance of the amber fort, up the steep slope. it is definitely a ride worth taking.

the elephant ride up the steep hill commences from the car parking lot and ends at the courtyard of the amber fort. the total duration of the trip is estimated to be around 20 to 30 minutes. the trip duration varies from elephant to elephant and also on the traffic. the cost of taking an elephant ride up this hill is approximately inr 1000 for two. you can enjoy the setting sun while sitting on the back of an elephant. this mesmeric view would enthral your senses and would surely give you a taste of royalty to experience. these elephants carry around 900 - 1000 visitors per day, and there are about 80 - 90 elephants in the service. the rajasthan government conducts regular checks to ensure the safety and the welfare of these animals. these checks have been implemented to ensure the safety and limit the cruelty to these animals.

__label__Iceland i have this habit of almost missing flights on the end of a trip. it's seems more often than not the best weather is the day i depart. many all night road trips seem to end with a pack-as-you-drive rush to catch my flight. .
. 
my last trip was thwarted with bad weather all the way until the night before. these rhyolite mountains had been on my list for years to see, so with a few hours of decent weather and clear road conditions we headed out. but if there is one thing you learn in iceland it's to never trust the weather forecast. we took in this view for 30 minutes before freezing rain set in & the entire area was covered in mist. you couldn't see 10 ft in front of you. as if nothing was even there. i've realized that one of best things about traveling is having something worth coming back for. .
@_ryanhill_ @icelandair

__label__Hawaii the king kamehameha statue stands proudly near downtown hilo in the wailoa river state park. it is one of four statues of king kamehameha i. the other three are located in kohala on the big island of hawaii, in downtown honolulu on the island of oahu, and in statuary hall in washington, d.c.

king kamehameha i, also known as kamehameha the great, who was born 1758 or 1737 or 1738 (there is some debate as to the precise year of his birth) and who died in 1819, was one of the most beloved of hawaii's heroes. kamehameha i was the one who conquered the hawaiian islands, unified them and established the kingdom of hawaii in 1810. even during times of intense western influence, his government managed to maintain peace and the traditional values. he developed alliances with the major pacific colonial powers and by doing so preserved hawaii's independence.

__label__Utah i love when a post stirs opinions, like this one. it means people are forced to deal with an ideology or thought process that is different than their own & choose to agree, disagree or educate. i don't ride motorcycles but have a massive respect for that do & understand the need for people to enjoy access to open land for a variety of uses. one of the biggest issues i see is that trying to take a one sided approach to how we use these places alienates many people and interest groups. continuing with this "i'm right, you're wrong" mindset when it comes to public space is what has divided us thus far. although it's a beautiful idea that all nature could be preserved and left in a perfect state ( in a perfect world it would be) it's not the case for us & that also alienates the way some people enjoy land. although this ^ is more disruptive than putting bolts on a wall, taking non native animals outdoors, the romanticized idea of livestock/ farming or creating a mtn bike or hiking trial.. all damage nature in some small way. keep in mind every road we drive on was once unspoiled nature. our homes stand on land that belonged to someone else and may have displaced wildlife. 
for those who have a mind set that this is "just for likes" or some idiotic rhetoric - this place is a long standing and widely used atv and off road area used by thousands and widely enjoyed. photos & videos of it are all over. i share work here i have shot personally and commercially and i can guarantee that my interest in people’s ‘likes’ is the least motivating force behind what i shoot and share. i would implore you to think before speaking, commenting and try to understand the motivation behind such a post. if people did the smallest bit of research they would understand that my greatest goal is to challenge how people think and view roles in the environment. doing that doesn’t always mean you embrace popular opinion.———————————— .

original caption: 
equal importance should be placed on creating places where people can play as much as protect.

__label__PlanetEarth over the years the idea of living self sustained has become more & more important to me. or maybe i'm just wanting to rely less on things i personally can't control. we run our office off solar, house from a well pump & leach field, raise chickens & ducks and in the past have grown many to most of our own veggies. what we can't make ourselves we try to borrow from friends & neighbors. none of it is easy.. ever & it won't begging to offset the carbon footprint - but its a start. 
its a process to constantly look for ways we can be less dependent on others for power, food & waste. it will never be flawless & its always been an investment, but its one worth making for a brighter future.
.

this dome & other dwellings have always been a beautiful representation to me of impermanent structures leaving little to no trace.

__label__Verona,Italy surprise! @anna.everywhere and i are moving to italy next month! 🇮🇹 @poofythefluffycat is coming too. 🐈
-
we’ve decided on the northern italian city of #verona, after visiting earlier this year. we tried colorado, california, and texas, but just didn’t find what we were looking for in the states. so now we’re off to give italy a go!
-
we both have eu passports (i have dual citizenship in ireland now) and we both work online, which makes moving to europe possible. we picked verona because it’s a pretty town that’s not too big but not too small, a short train ride away from larger cities, and very close to the italian dolomites, some of the best mountains in europe.
-
so it’s back to being an expat for a while! i guess i’ll have to start learning italian... 🤓

__label__LosAngeles,California お気に入りになったヨガスタジオ。沢山のグルとハヌマンがセンターで見守っている。

サンタモニカで受ける最後のヨガはもう頑張らず、yinヨガ・癒され系で締めようとスケジュールをたてた。
on timeに間に合うように準備していたところ、今日からルームメイトになった
ドクターをしている旅好きロシア女子が、ガンガンに話しかけてくる。
彼女との会話は何だか楽しい。だが、もういかねば。
会ってすぐ、ロサンゼルスに来て何をしたかを聞かれ、「ヨガしかしてない、ロスではサンタモニカから出てない」と言うと驚かれていたのだが、
会話をひと段落させ「私は今から夜のヨガに行ってくる」と告げると、
呆れたように、「ヨガー！？ユー アー クレイジー」と笑われた。

少し遅刻してスタジオに。部屋に入ってビックリ。
スケジュールには、インヨガ ５エレメンツ with サウンド バスとあったので、
どんな音のシャワーを浴びながらのヨガだろうとワクワクしていたが、
何と私が自分のヨガやヒーリングで使っているクリスタルボウルがセットされていた。
自分が奏でてもらうのは、今までにバリで数回だけ。奏でながら、みんな気持ち良さそうなので私もたまには受ける側になりたいと思っている。
何てこった。最後にこんなスペシャルご褒美。完璧なシナリオ。
クリスタルボウルの音色でのインヨガは、それはそれは癒され、ここまでの道のりの疲れが癒された。それはこの旅だけのことではなく。
そして今後の閃きも貰い、受けて側の人の体験もさせて貰えた。

ヨガが終わった後、演奏者の人が「よかったらオラクルカードをひいて」というので
一枚選ぶ。色んな宗教の神様や天使のカードがあるらしい。
中から私がひいたのは、なんとも！インドの女神ラクシュミー。
カードの意味をbookで読ませてもらう。
美と豊かさ、目標達成や繁栄を司る女神ラクシュミーからのメッセージは、
自分の価値を認める事と、
不安や自分の経験の中からリミットを作るのではなく、限界のない恩恵を受け取りなさいというようなことだった。
まさにセドナでそんな風にマインドをシフトさせたばかりだったので、
まるでこの旅の終わりに、おさらいのメッセージだ。
素敵な時間を頂けたこと、帰りに心からのサンキューを言った。
まだまだこのスタジオに通いたかったけど、最後に旅の締めらしい時間を過ごせたので、
悔い無く納得してスタジオを後にした。

__label__Philippines mornings by the sea ✵

walking barefoot along a glossy beach, beside a glassy ocean, waiting for pastel skies to clear. cool, calm, humid. suspended in this limbo between dawn and day, the wet laps of waves, a wink from the sun. tension. anticipation. then the clouds melt away, the sun blazes down, the day is arrived. cockerels begin to crow. dogs begin to bark. engine motors begin to splutter. the moment is gone. 
there’s no sunrise like a philippine sunrise, for me. tell us, where’s the most beautiful place you’ve seen the sun rise over the ocean? :::

__label__Zanzibar,Tanzania ask me anything 🤔
q3 by @jenygoesplaces - "years down this journey, what do you feel about the life you left? do you see yourself going back to a job and settling down at a place?"
.
.
i sometimes think of my two years of corporate life, the 9 to 5 routine, working with a great team on social media strategies, of the money that landed up in my account every month without fail... and i compare it to my current life, that gives me the freedom to pick up my bags and leave for where my heart longs, to stay as long as i want in far off corners of the world, to have created a living out of something i love (writing and social media), of the money that sometimes shows up and sometimes doesn't. both lifestyles have their pros and cons, but i know the latter is for me, i choose freedom and adventure over  stability and money.
.
.
to everyone who asks me what i'm chasing with all this travel, i want to ask what we are chasing in a "regular" life? if we are chasing a (false) sense of security through a steady job and a legal relationship and a house we own, then that's exactly what i aspire to run from. from the illusion that i control my life and the future. .
.
the road is like a mirror for my personal life. you know all those friendships and relationships we bank on? when you're always away, you learn which of your relationships are real enough to survive time and distance. so i might have much fewer "real" relationships now - some from my earlier life, some from the road - but they feel so much more real to me than a room full of pseudo friends. .
.
i don't see myself working 9 to 5 again, or for someone else. but i do dream of a place where i can maybe spend 6 months every year, surrounded by nature, grow my own produce and start a sustainable travel initiative... so far, it's just a distant dream 😇
.
.
and you, what does your journey in life currently look like? what are you chasing?
.
.

__label__Barcelona,Spain today the unthinkable happened in barcelona happened - it rained! lol it actually wasn't bad for what i wanted to see and do and it even added a nice moody touch to a planned lunch along the beach with my other @aktravel_usa participants. funny thing about barcelona's long sandy shorefront; it didn't exist before the 1992 olympic games. those games were actually a turning point for the city, forcing it into long overdo improvements including moving the massive industries once located along the water and turning it into the sunny beachside residents never thought they'd see. so that's why, sun or not, spending time along barcelona's beaches isn't just fun, it's a big part of the overall city experience. #aktravel

__label__Lima,Peru hey y'all! just your friendly reminder this valentine's day -- that being single doesn't suck, it's your mentality that does.

the happiness you're trying to find in someone else should be rooted internally first.

if you're looking for someone to complete you, you've bought into the flawed ideology that you're inadequate on your own.

you will never find happiness in someone else if you can't learn to be happy on your own first.

so treat yourself to your favorite meal.
binge-watch your favorite show.
and most importantly, fall asleep diagonally.

oh, and pro tip for the men: if your lady says you don't have to get her anything on valentine's day, it is the biggest trap of all time and i hope you didn't fall for it.

__label__London,UnitedKingdom ✨covent garden ✨is a district of london on the eastern edge of the west end. covent garden is london's marketplace for art and culture. with its street cafés, the nearby royal opera house and the many artists who transform the square into an open-air stage, it stands for pure joie de vivre and radiates italian flair.🎭🤹‍♀️🎻🤹‍♂️🎷🎸🤹‍♂️🎭🎺✨
in the middle ages there was already a market there. since 1830 there is a big market hall. with its iron construction and glass roof, it is still the showpiece of the square today.
there are a lot of restaurants, bars and cafes where you just sit down and watch the artists.☕️🍦🍰🍩✨ especially on weekends there is always something on offer in the covent garden market and the market halls become a circus management or an opera house. many music students play concerts there at a high level and hope to be discovered. ✨i love it there!✨😍😍😍
the next tube station is covent garden.

__label__Havana,Cuba #traveltip of the week:  havana is one of our absolute favorite cities in the world – how stunning is this central square? with it’s combination of exquisite european style architecture, colorful facades, and streets filled with the sounds of live salsa, havana is one of the most lively places that we’ve visited. many americans think that it’s off limits to visit, but that’s not the case. we’re passionate about helping people experience the real cuba. ask us how! 📷: our founder, @adventurousarah

__label__CurrumbinBeach good morning!! finally got out for sunrise today and managed to give a photography lesson to @two4two_photography !! keep an eye on his feed later on today to see what he came up with. we covered slow shutter, sunrise, depth of field and fast shutter. i always take and teach sunrise the same way. iso 100, f11 in manual mode. my shutter here was 1/6 but i always bracket one stop on either side to get my favorite shot. using the nikon d600 and the brand new 24-70 f2.8 lens. loving it!!
